By JON FRANK Phil Kellam rides in the back seat of a 1999 Ford Expedition, alternately using his cell phone and his laptop while his communications director drives the rain-slicked roads of Virginia Beach. Kellam is between campaign stops, electronically working the network of Democratic supporters that is trying to help him unseat U.S. Rep. Thelma Drake, the first-term Republican congresswoman from Norfolk who represents Virginia's 2nd District. Kellam, the Virginia Beach revenue commissioner, who is the only elected Democrat in the city, plans to address residents of a Beach senior citizens home and then speak to a luncheon of Kiwanis Club members in Norfolk. "This is a traveling office," Kellam says, as the Expedition heads down Shore Drive. "I don't see how people could run a campaign being only in one place." It's electioneering, 21st-century style. But one thing hasn't changed, says Kellam as he completes one phone conversation and begins punching in another number. "At the end of the day, if you are asking somebody for $1,000, you have to do it personally." Kellam, 50, a Beach native who looks 10 years younger than his age, has been doing a lot of that in 2006. With blond hair and the carriage of an athlete, Kellam has the relaxed demeanor of a surfer who hops on the road on the spur of the moment to surf Hatteras Island or Wrightsville Beach. The surf culture that helped shape Kellam still exerts an influence. When time and ocean conditions allow, Kellam will ride the occasional wave with sons Alex, 18, and Jay, 8. The problem is, these days, there is no time. Despite being a member of a legendary and political Beach family, with connections that go back several generations of voters, Kellam has been way behind in fundraising since the beginning of this congressional campaign. He's trying to unseat an incumbent with strong ties to the Bush administration, and it's an uphill struggle. Kellam works on a speech inside his campaign headquarters off Witchduck Road in Virginia Beach. At the end of September, Kellam's $1.1 million total had been nearly doubled by Drake, who raised just less than $2 million to set a record for 2nd District races, according to her campaign staff. That hasn't deterred Kellam, who has had some celebrity help of his own. Bestselling author John Grisham, who lives some of the year near Charlottesville, has contributed to Kellam's campaign, and House Minority Whip Steny Hoyer of Maryland visited the district during the summer to lend a hand. Kellam hopes to capitalize on the problems in Iraq and scandals within the GOP's congressional leadership. Several polls taken near the end of the summer showed Kellam and Drake nearly deadlocked. The polls have energized local Democrats into believing that Kellam can win in a district heavy with active-duty and retired military and a Republican stronghold for six years. "The public gets it," Kellam says with confidence as the Expedition pulls into Westminster Canterbury, where Kellam's mother, Alice, lives with other well-to-do senior citizens. "The public knows what kind of operator I am, and my track record. The public knows that I am sincere." Kellam has been building his record since 1997, when he was first elected commissioner of revenue. He made his mark by doing what nearly every taxpayer wants done: He reduced staff by 24 percent, increased productivity, and took up less space at the municipal center. He also got rid of the city sticker, a move that streamlined city government at the Beach, and elsewhere, as other localities followed suit. "He should take some pride in that," said John T. Atkinson, the Republican Virginia Beach treasurer who opposed the sticker removal but now acknowledges it was a good move. The information formerly gathered by the sticker is now collected when license plates are renewed at the Department of Motor Vehicles, said Eric Schmudde, Kellam's chief deputy. The productivity boost, Schmudde said, has been achieved, in part, by automation. When Kellam took office, there were 20 computers and 85 employees, he said; the office now has 90 computers and 61 employees. Kellam also opened the DMV's first satellite office, which allows most driver-related tasks, except license renewal, to be done at the commissioner of revenue office, Schmudde said. Critics of Kellam say his accomplishments are overrated. Kellam campaigns in late August at Westminster Canterbury on Chesapeake Bay, in Virginia Beach, where his mother is a resident. The sticker fee is still collected by the state. And the budget cuts were achieved by getting rid of long-term employees and replacing them with newcomers, they said. They wonder more about the unanswered question in Kellam's candidacy: how big a role the Kellam family name will play in the election. His paternal grandfather, Abel E. Kellam, was clerk of the court for Princess Anne County and had 17 children. One of his 15 sons, Sidney, was a key player in the Byrd organization, the Democratic Party's 20th-century political dynasty in Virginia. As treasurer, Sidney was considered the political leader in Princess Anne County for 40 years. Two of the Kellam brothers were judges. Floyd was on the Circuit Court, and Phil's father, Richard, was on the U.S. District Court. Another brother, Bill, was a state senator. Today, the family name appears on street signs, businesses and schools. Phil remembers being asked, while a student at Kellam High School, whether he owned the place. Phil Kellam is the only one of the 26 Kellam cousins who has gone into politics. "I wanted to be as far away from it as possible," said Phil's older sister, Martha Kellam Stone. Her brother, however, always seemed "fascinated" by politics, Stone said. "He used to talk a lot to Uncle Sidney," she remembered. "I thought he probably would end up in politics." Kellam attended boarding school in Richmond, finished at Kellam High and then went to Elon College in North Carolina, where he majored in political science and met his future wife, Andi. The couple raised their two sons at the Kellam family homestead until their divorce in 2004 after 21 years of marriage. Andi said their family relationship remains strong, especially around Christmas, a time that Kellam loves and tries to extend whenever possible. "I remember telling him once: 'It's almost Valentine's Day. Don't you think we ought to take the Christmas decorations down?' " Andi recalled. Local Republicans concede that the Kellam name is formidable, especially in Virginia Beach, where the vast majority of 2nd District voters resides. But the city no longer has the demographic makeup it had in Sidney Kellam's day, said Bruce Meyer, the 2nd District chairman for the Republicans. Newcomers, he said, are more familiar with the name through Kellam High School, which was named after Circuit Judge Floyd Kellam, Phil 's uncle. Kellam heads out the back door of his home in Virginia Beach. It is where, this fall, he hosted an event known as the Elephant Roast a swipe at the GOP symbol. Atkinson, Virginia Beach's treasurer for 28 years, and once the only elected Republican in Virginia Beach, said the Kellam family name still carries clout, but "this is a Republican city." When Virginia Beach and Princess Anne County were run by Democrats, it was the Kellam family home on Princess Anne Road that symbolized political power. Phil Kellam still lives there. It is only a short walk away from the commissioners office he runs. But Kellam has another reason to love the multistory, white frame homestead, nestled in a grove of pine, oak and magnolia trees. Each fall he hosts a political event there known as the Elephant Roast, a dig at the GOP's big-eared symbol and an event open only to Democrats. At this year's event, Kellam spoke only briefly, recalling that the Kellam legacy still permeates the old homestead. Growing up where scores of political careers began and ended shaped him, he said, and continues to drive his desire to remain in politics. "In the family that I grew up in, we were taught to do something about our community if we thought we could make a difference," Kellam said during an interview. "I saw what you could do if you got involved in public life." Edwin Kellam, one of his cousins, believes Kellam made the right choice. "He absolutely loves what he does," Edwin Kellam said, "being with people, and the politics." Kellam understands that Congress is a huge responsibility, even for someone who loves the arena of public policy and has an especially strong component of political DNA coursing through his veins. "My life is pretty darn good," Kellam said as his Expedition pulled away from the Kiwanis Club luncheon. "So why would I want to endure all of this and run for office every two years? Because it needs to be done. If not me, then who?" Reach Jon Frank at or PHILIP J. It has been a season Booker T. Washington coach Larry Stepney would rather forget. The Bookers (1-5) are off to their worst start since 2000, when they finished 2-8. But Stepney's pain extends beyond the field. Since Aug. 23, he has had back spasms caused by a car accident. He was hospitalized for high blood pressure and missed the Bookers' game against Deep Creek. He's now battling a sinus infection and gout in his right foot. "We had a week off two weeks ago, and I started to get myself together," said Stepney, 53. "Then all of a sudden, gout hit. My foot swelled, so that I was on crutches last week during the Churchland game. I get one thing repaired, and something else comes up." Stepney, in his 15th season at Booker T. Washington, said retiring has crossed his mind. But he doesn't want to end his coaching career like this. "I'm going to weigh the situation and talk to my wife, and then make a decision from there," he said. "But I really don't want to go out this way. I can't go out like this. "If I do come back next year, it will be my last unless something else comes up where I can just coach." Stepney, who missed practice Monday because of his foot and sinuses, expects to be on the sideline Thursday when the Bookers play Maury. Stepney's team can't catch a break, either The old adage "when it rains, it pours" definitely has hit Booker T. Washington. With coach Larry Stepney already ailing and on crutches as the Bookers prepared to play Churchland, they also learned before the game that standout tight end/linebacker Adidias Arrington dislocated his jaw on the bus ride to the game. Arrington, a 6-foot-2, 205-pound senior, fell asleep on the bus. When he woke up and yawned, his jaw popped. "This kid has muscles everywhere," Stepney said. "And out of all the muscles to relax, it was his jaw muscle." Oscar Smith freshman to be at QB vs. Deep Creek Oscar Smith freshman Phillip Sims likely will get his third consecutive start at quarterback when the top-ranked Tigers take on No. 3 Deep Creek in a Southeastern District game Friday pitting a pair of unbeaten teams. Sims has started the past two games in place of star Dexter Merritt, a senior who suffered a third-degree medial collateral right knee sprain Sept. 29 against Western Branch. "Dexter's walking well, and he's pretty mobile right now, but he hasn't been cleared to play," Oscar Smith coach Richard Morgan said Tuesday. "So right now Sims is the guy getting all the reps, and Dex is at practice watching and helping him out." Sims threw just one pass in relief of Merritt against Western Branch but has been impressive in victories over Granby and Nansemond River. Sims has completed 25 of 36 passes for six touchdowns and 460 yards, with no interceptions. Barring a remarkable turnaround by Merritt, Sims will be behind center Friday in a match-up the Tigers won 24-21 last season. "Dex would have to show some more mobility, and right now I'm not holding out hope that he's going to play this week," Morgan said. "We're putting in the game plan with Phillip this week." Indian River QB Poittilo might return this week Another Southeastern District starting QB could return to the field Friday. Indian River's Dravon Poittilo's status will be a "game-time decision," according to coach Cadillac Harris, whose team hosts Lakeland. Poittilo missed Saturday's loss against Lake Taylor after suffering a concussion in Indian River's previous game. Poittilo joins a list of walking wounded for the Braves, who have been plagued by injuries since a season-opening upset of Hampton. Indian River was without two starting wide receivers in a loss to Deep Creek, and Harris said a "rash of concussions" hit the Braves in recent weeks. Starting defensive tackle Quincy Davis also was one of four players who missed Saturday's game. Despite 0-6 record, Hudak not looking back Granby coach Dave Hudak insists he has no regrets. Last March, he accepted the head-coaching position at Landstown only to change his mind a month later and return to Granby. The Eagles are 5-2 this season - the Comets are 0-6. "I'm happy for them, but my decision wasn't based on who was going to have the better season," said Hudak, now in his 21st season at Granby. "You never anticipate starting off the season with six losses, but I also knew there would be some growing pains because we had to move people around from positions they normally play.. But we're improving every day." Hudak said it's good that he returned because he said a new coach would have been frustrated by the start. "I'm right where I want to be," Hudak said. "I've got Granby running through me, and there's no other place I'd rather be." But for how long? "When I came back, I was thinking I'd stay for two more years," he said. "But (Granby administrators) keep talking about two or three years. We'll play it by ear. Right now the plan is this year, next year, and then we'll see." Tallwood QB determined to play no matter what For those who aren't paying attention, Tallwood has the second-best record in the Beach District at 5-1. "It sounds pretty good, but we still have four games left, so we can't too excited yet," Lions QB Brian Jackson said. "We have the power to control our destiny.. Hopefully we can keep playing like we're playing right now." Jackson had another big game in leading the Lions past Kempsville 23-17. He completed 10 of 18 passes for 185 yards and a touchdown. He accomplished all of this despite a bad cut to his throwing hand. He injured the hand, which required 10 stitches, on the first play of the game. He thinks he cut it on an opposing player's helmet. "I didn't want to go out after the first play," he said. "There was still 47 minutes left, and anything could happen. I could worry about my hand after the game." Jackson said the injury will not keep him out of Friday's home game against Cox. "Nothing is going to hold me back from playing," he said. "I could have a broken hand, and I'm still going to try my best to play." Deep Creek announcer jumped gun on Kirkland Deep Creek QB Sam Kirkland said it was just a slip. Kirkland, a senior, was participating in Deep Creek's homecoming ceremonies last Friday when the public address announcer proclaimed that Kirkland would attend Maryland on a football scholarship. The news was received with a huge ovation. But not so fast. Kirkland, a 6-foot, 190-pounder, said he has not made his college decision. He said he is interested in a list of schools that includes Syracuse, N.C. State, Maryland, Virginia Tech, South Carolina, Tennessee, UNC, East Carolina, Penn State, Marshall and James Madison. He added that Madison is the only program that has offered him a scholarship. Madison also is the only one interested in him as a quarterback. "Most schools want me as a defensive back or wide receiver," he said. "I'll be happy with any place that can use my athletic ability." At the moment, the only thing on Kirkland's mind is Friday's game against top-ranked Oscar Smith. "I've been waiting on this game all year," Kirkland said. "It's our rival, and a lot is at stake. They've beaten us the last three years, but we feel we can play with them. We'll see what happens on Friday." TD was a dream come true for Salem's Okoli Chimaeze Okoli, Salem's 6-foot-5, 275-pound defensive end, couldn't believe his eyes. Okoli was rushing the passer during the first quarter of Friday's game against Landstown when he saw the football hit the ground. "That was surreal to me," Okoli said. "It felt like it almost didn't happen." It did, and Okoli scooped up the fumble and lumbered 10 yards for a touchdown. The score gave Salem a three-touchdown lead and helped propel the unbeaten Sun Devils to a 42-2 victory. Okoli had 2-1/2 sacks and recovered two fumbles, but he won't soon forget his first career touchdown. "The ball popped right to me," Okoli said. "I tell you, I dream about that so much. That's every single D-lineman's dream. I didn't even know what to do." - Compiled by Larry Rubama and Jami Frankenberry

text: This winter's General Assembly session largely was about money and lessons learned from the Virginia Tech tragedy. Cash was tight and lawmakers had to extend the session five days beyond their scheduled adjournment before they agreed on a two-year, $77 billion budget that will go into effect July 1. Nobody got all they wanted. Teachers will receive a 2 percent raise in July 2009. State employees and college faculty members will get 2 percent boosts at the end of this year and next. Six hundred new community care openings will be created for the mentally disabled. The state will spend $22 million to expand prekindergarten programs for children from low-income families. There was no money left to aid museums and cultural programs. Local governments will take a 5 percent cut in state funding. Lawmakers are still searching for dollars to improve transportation in South Hampton Roads and Northern Virginia. The General Assembly, with many of its members unwilling to vote to raise taxes, is expected take up road funding in a special session this spring. Thoughts never strayed far from Virginia Tech, where a gunman with a history of psychological problems killed 32 students and faculty members before committing suicide April 16. Lawmakers approved a $42 million revamping of the mental health system and broadened the threshold for involuntarily committing a people to institutions. Still left to be done in special sessions to be held in late April will be attempts to find a compromise on how to pay for major transportation projects in Hampton Roads and Northern Virginia. Legislators also hope to reach an agreement on judicial appointments. Here are the fates of some of the bills that were considered by the General Assembly this year. Detailed information about each bill is available on the General Assembly's Web site: -IMMIGRATION- PASSED No bail. Presumption against bail for illegal immigrants charged with serious crimes (SB623, HB440). In custody. Requires jail employees to inquire about inmates' citizenship (SB609, HB820). Signed by Gov. Timothy M. Kaine. Employer penalty. Terminates business license for one year if business hires illegal immigrants (HB926). FAILED Speaking English. Protects employers from discrimination lawsuits for firing people who can't or don't speak English on the job (HB1472). Local role. Requires local law enforcement to help enforce federal immigration laws through federal 287(g) program (HB623). Crime victims. Prohibits police from asking victims about immigration status (SB441). Name changes. Applicants would have to prove U.S. citizenship to apply for a name change (HB151). Higher education. Bars illegal immigrants from attending state colleges and universities (HB14). Denies in-state tuition to illegal immigrants (SB652). -ENVIRONMENT- PASSED Computer recycling. Requires computer equipment manufacturers to collect, recycle and reuse computer equipment (HB344). Energy and climate. Establishes the Virginia Commission on Energy and Climate Change as a legislative commission to promote conservation and alternative energy sources (SB464). FAILED Uranium mining study. Proposal to study whether uranium can be mined safely in Virginia (SB525). Greenhouse gas. Requires state air pollution control board to adopt regulations requiring mandatory reporting of greenhouse gas emissions from stationary sources (SB234). Green building. Requires state agencies to design facilities to meet energy and environmental design criteria; phased in over three years based on square footage of project. Does not apply to public school districts (SB447). CARRIED OVER TO 2009 Greenhouse gas. Requires statewide transportation plan to include quantifiable measures and achievable goals for greenhouse gas emissions (SB233). -TAXES- FAILED Gas tax increase. Increase motor fuel by a penny a gallon each year for five years. The revenue is to pay for the upkeep of Virginia's road network (SB713). Energy-efficient homes. People who build and buy EarthCraft homes, noted for being energy-efficient and environmentally friendly, would get a one-time $500 tax credit (SB317). CARRIED OVER TO 2009 Residential real estate tax exemption. Amends the state constitution to allow localities to adopt laws to exempt or defer up to 20 percent of real estate taxes on homes, known as the "homestead exemption." Voters would have to approve the amendment in November (HB11). -PUBLIC SAFETY- PASSED Drunken driving. Requires the implementation of ignition interlock for a violation of the conditions of a DUI restricted license (HB1442). New penalty for underage drinking. Provides "zero tolerance" for underage motorists with .02 blood-alcohol concentration, punishable as a Class 1 misdemeanor. Penalty rises from a six-month license forfeiture to one year, and the fine would be a mandatory minimum fine of $500 or 50 hours of community service (HB719). Guns. Requires that a person seeking to purchase a firearm from a firearms dealer answer questions on the state background check consent form concerning whether the applicant has ever been acquitted by reason of insanity, been adjudicated legally incompetent or mentally incapacitated, or been involuntarily admitted to a facility or involuntarily ordered to outpatient mental health treatment (SB226). Sex offenders. Prevents sex offenders from going into or being within 100 feet of a public recreation center unless they are picking up their own child (HB223). No alcohol for gangs. Allows the state regulators to revoke an establishment license to sell alcohol if the location becomes a meeting place for a criminal street gang (HB1117). Signed by Kaine. FAILED Gun-show sales. Would have prevented private vendors from selling weapons at gun shows without background checks (HB745, SB109). The Virginia State Crime Commission is to study the issue. Drunken driving. Sets minimum fine for DUI offense at $2,250 and fines for vehicle-related felonies at $2,500 to $3,000 (HB161). Death penalty. Allows for people other than the "triggerman" who are an accomplice to a capital murder to be eligible for death penalty (HB933). Passed General Assembly but vetoed by Kaine. -EDUCATION- PASSED Cell phones on school buses. Drivers would be prohibited from using mobile phones while operating school buses, except in an emergency, when the vehicle is parked or for dispatching purposes (HB1218). Signed by Kaine. Felony drug crime or sexual abuse by school employees. Requires the court clerks to notify the Superintendent of Public Instruction when a person known to be licensed by the Board of Education is convicted of a felony drug crime or certain felony sex crimes involving a child victim. Local school systems would be required to create procedures to handle complaints of sexual abuse made by students against teachers or other school employees (HB1439). FAILED Fatty foods. School superintendents would be required to develop guidelines to eliminate cooking ingredients and foods containing trans fat from public school cafeterias and vending machines (SB124). -SOCIAL ISSUES- PASSED Animal fighting. Increases penalties for animal fighting, including dogfighting and cockfighting (HB656, SB592). Lie detector. Prohibits asking victims of sex crimes to take a polygraph test as a condition for an investigation (SB164, HB1043). FAILED Abortion. Requires abortion clinics to meet same standards as outpatient surgery centers (HB894). Requires doctors performing abortions to offer ultrasound picture (HB1315). Requires doctors to offer woman anesthetic for fetus (HB1556). A woman who uses drugs or weapon to kill her unborn baby would be guilty of a Class 4 felony (HB1126). Domestic partner health benefits. Would provide local governments the ability to extend employee health benefits to some domestic partnerships (SB51). CARRIED OVER TO 2009 Abortion. Causing a miscarriage through reckless behavior would be a Class 5 felony (HB312). -CONSUMER ISSUES- PASSED Payday loans. Bills in the House and Senate would place new regulations on payday lenders. The House version would require lenders to check an Internet database of clients before issuing loans; limit borrowers to one loan at a time and five within 180 days; place a 36 percent interest rate cap on loans; and extend the loan repayment period. Lender fees on loans would also increase to 20 percent of the loan amount, plus a $5 filing fee (HB12, SB588). Identity theft protection. Businesses that operate in Virginia would be required to provide notice of a computer database breach to affected individuals and the appropriate authorities (SB307, HB1469). Short reprieve on foreclosures. Requires lenders to notify delinquent borrowers 10 business days before starting foreclosure proceedings. Borrowers can request more time and lenders would have to wait 30 days before seeking payment (SB797). -TRANSPORTATION- PASSED Bad driver fees. Repeals abusive driver fees that can be assessed against motorists convicted of certain driving offenses. Fees are as high as $3,000 in cases. Those charged the fees would get a refund of any fees already paid and would have any outstanding balances forgiven by courts (SB1, HB1243). FAILED Seat belts. Would make driving without a seat belt a primary offense, meaning police could stop a driver for failure to wear the safety restraint. It is currently a secondary offense (SB649). CARRIED OVER TO 2009 Vehicle inspections. Gov. Timothy M. Kaine had proposed shifting car inspections from an annual requirement to one that must be done every other year (SB526). -MILITARY- PASSED Military personnel. Deadlines for driver's license renewal, license plate registration, local vehicle registration, property tax, and other state and local tax filings extended until 90 days after return from deployment for military personnel (HB1024). Virginia Military Parents Equal Protection Act. Limits a court's authority to permanently modify orders regarding the custody or visitation of a child because of a parent's deployment status (SB188). Veteran-owned businesses. Aligns Virginia's eligibility requirements for participation in the Service-Disabled Veteran-Owned Small Business Program with federal eligibility requirements (HB1386). -HEALTH ISSUES- FAILED Smoking. Allows localities to adopt ordinances relating to smoking in restaurants that meet or exceed those established in the Virginia Indoor Clean Air Act (SB202). Prohibits smoking in all indoor restaurants and bar and lounge areas in the commonwealth (SB501). Prohibits smoking indoors in most buildings or enclosed areas frequented by the public (SB298). Provides that any locality within Hampton Roads may adopt an ordinance regulating smoking in restaurants (SB347). HPV vaccine. Extends the effective date of the requirement for sixth-grade girls to receive the human papillomavirus vaccine from October 2008 to July 2010 (HB188). -FREEDOM OF INFORMATION- PASSED School donors. Would allow donors to state colleges and universities to be kept anonymous (HB407). Secret work. Exempts from public disclosure all records related to "criminal intelligence" and "terrorism investigation" generated by the Virginia Fusion Intelligence Center, a State Police-run anti-terrorism division (HB1007). CARRIED OVER TO 2009 Gun database. Bars public access to statewide list of concealed-gun-permit holders maintained by Virginia State Police (HB982). -MENTAL HEALTH- PASSED Parental consent. Parents could admit minor child for inpatient treatment if the minor is incapable of giving consent (SB67). Signed by Kaine. Petition for involuntary commitment of a minor should be served upon minor or a parent unless it's withdrawn or dismissed (SB68). Signed by Kaine. Involuntary commitment. Person may be involuntarily committed or placed in temporary custody if substantial likelihood exists that mental illness will cause harm to self or others (SB246). Court should appoint lawyer and guardian for minors facing involuntary commitment hearings if minor is 14 or older and objects to inpatient treatment (SB247). Increases to 96 hours the time allowed to hold a hearing for involuntary commitment of a minor or emergency admission of a minor to inpatient treatment (SB276). Outpatient treatment. Sets length of initial mandatory outpatient treatment at 90 days, and allows follow-up treatment orders of 180 days. Also requires community service board to report noncompliance with ordered treatment to the court (HB499). Ending the use of "retardation." The term "mental retardation" would be replaced in the state laws and in the state code with the term "intellectual disability." FAILED Parental consent. Requires parent or guardian of a minor to be notified that their child has had mental health treatment within five days of the service, unless such information could cause substantial harm to the minor or another person (HB121). -HAMPTON ROADS- PASSED State audit of SPSA finances. Requires an audit of the Southeastern Public Service Authority by the state auditor of public accounts. The report is due back next year (HJ89). ABC stores. Would allow Sunday sales at some state liquor stores in Chesapeake, Portsmouth, Hampton and Newport News (HB908). Signed by Kaine. FAILED Craney Island study. Would have required study on the impact of increasing size and dredging around Craney Island (HJ117).

No. 4 Maury 29, Great Bridge 22 NORFOLK - Maury scored 14 fourth-quarter points to win its eighth in a row, this one a non-district game Friday at Powhatan Field, and move closer to locking up a Division 5 playoff berth. Early in the fourth quarter, Commodores quarterback Stephen Kelley tied the score at 22 with a 14-yard TD run. The Wildcats (3-6) drove to the Maury 14 on the ensuing possession, but Dyrri McCain intercepted a pass that bounced off Logan Cobell's shoulder pad. Seven plays later, Lorenzo Branche scored the winning TD for Maury (8-1). Key stats: M-Kelley 11-19-1-315, 2 TDs passing; 9-25, TD rushing; James Butts 7-143 receiving; McCain 1-76 receiving, INT. GB-Casey Turner 26-45-2-247, 3 TDs passing; Carlos Washington 9-105, TD receiving, 14-45 rushing; David Reynolds 4-51 receiving. - Reported by Gary Lassiter No. 10 Kellam 35, Ocean Lakes 28 VIRGINIA BEACH - Patrick Harrington and Greg Nosal scored two TDs each as the Knights came from behind to win a Beach District game. The Dolphins took a 14-7 first-quarter lead behind two TD runs by Marcus Davis. Harrington scored on a 35-yard catch and a 2-yard run as Kellam (7-2) went up 21-14. The Dolphins then drove 73 yards to the Kellam 1, but Davis was stopped at the 1 as time expired in the first half. Matt Ritt and Nosal teamed up on 29- and 7-yard touchdown passes in the second half as Kellam went up 35-21. After Ocean Lakes' Shamarko Thomas returned a fumble 30 yards to cut the margin to seven with 4:31 left, the Knights recovered an onside kick and ran out the clock. A 6-yard run for a first down by Biklen Jazexhiu on fourth-and-3 was key. Key stats: K-Jazexhiu 22-166 rushing; Ritt 6-8-1-122, 3 TDs passing; Nosal 3-53, 2 TDs receiving. OL-Davis 10-106, 2 TDs rushing; Dan Pitts 12-23-0-212, TD passing. He said it: "When we have a chance to throw the ball, we make the most of it. And having a target like Greg (Nosal) helps a lot." - Ritt - Reported by Brandt Bryant No. 3 Western Branch 45, Nansemond River 13 SUFFOLK - The Bruins used a smothering defense to dominate the Warriors in this Southeastern District game and set up a showdown next week with Deep Creek for a spot in the Division 6 playoffs. Derek Black intercepted two passes, running one back for a touchdown, and Western Branch (8-1, 6-1) held Nansemond River (2-8, 1-7) to minus 35 yards in the fourth quarter. Key stats: WB-Kevin Newsome 10-74, TD rushing; 5-11-0-164, TD passing; Laqwan Brodie 2-53 receiving. NR-Jamar Jerrell 11-81 rushing; Darryl Freeney 4-85, TD receiving. He said it: "We're just excited to have a chance to make the playoffs." - Bruins coach Lew Johnston, who is retiring after this season - Reported by Charlie Baumgardner No. 6 Deep Creek 37, Lakeland 13 SUFFOLK - Sam Kirkland threw two TD passes, and the Hornets (8-1, 6-1) amassed 389 yards of total offense in winning a Southeastern District game and setting up a showdown next Friday with rival Western Branch for a Division 6 playoff spot. Kirkland hooked up with Corey Harris on a 54-yard scoring pass and with Kosaun Dixon on a 10-yarder. The Cavaliers (1-8, 0-7) got on the board when Cedrick Johnson returned a fumble 73 yards for a touchdown in the third quarter. Key stats: DC-Calvin Wilson 12-92, TD rushing; Kadeem Young 4-76 rushing; Harris 4-113, TD receiving; Kirkland 7-11-0-146, 2 TDs passing. L-Dontarius Boone 7-62, TD rushing; Josh Meeks 14-24-1-113 passing; Asaad Graham 6-25 receiving; Chris Brown 3-31 receiving. - Reported by Dan Cooley No. 9 Landstown 48, Green Run 6 VIRGINIA BEACH - Sterlin Phifer ran for four TDs and 194 yards as the Eagles (7-2) rolled in this Beach District game and kept their Division 6 playoff hopes alive. Xavier Boyce also ran for a pair of TDs for Landstown. Tavon Gatlin had two interceptions for Green Run (1-9), which ended its season by losing its sixth straight. Key stats: L-Phifer 14-194, 4 TDs rushing; Boyce 4-39, TDs rushing. GR-Rahmel Glover 7-17-0-110, TD passing; Ronnie Dozier 3-72, TD receiving. - Reported by Sam Johnson First Colonial 28, Bayside 27 VIRGINIA BEACH - Freshman kicker Michael Mugler's extra point in overtime boosted the Patriots past the Marlins (5-4) in a Beach District game. The Patriots (5-4) overcame five turnovers. Bayside's Darrion Holloway opened overtime with a 10-yard touchdown run, but Casey Zeiders' extra-point attempt sailed wide right. First Colonial then twice handed the ball to Tony Gregory before Brandon Law scored on a 4-yard run, setting up Mugler's deciding kick. Mugler, who had missed his two previous extra-point attempts, was carried off the field by his teammates at game's end. Bayside took a 15-0 first-quarter lead before First Colonial answered with a safety and touchdown runs by Law, Gregory and Eric Hitch and led 21-15. The Marlins tied the score at 21 with four minutes left in the fourth quarter when Marquel Thomas hauled in a 64-yard touchdown pass from E.J. Manuel. However, Zeider's extra-point attempt was blocked. Key stats: B-Manuel 11-25-1-211, 2 TDs passing; Jamal Johnson 5-64 receiving; Deveon Braithwaite 3-60, TD rushing; Thomas 2-77, TD rushing. FC-Gregory 29-222, TD rushing; Law 10-49 rushing. He said it: "I liked it. They gave me more time to get ready." - Mugler after Bayside twice called timeout in attempts to ice him before his winning extra point - Reported by Alan Keck Indian River 27, King's Fork 17 CHESAPEAKE - Andre Fleming had a 79-yard TD run and scored on a 72-yard kickoff as the Braves won a Southeastern District game. QB Dravon Poittilo scored on a 1-yard run and connected with Fleming on a score as Indian River (5-4, 4-3) grabbed a 14-0 first-quarter lead. The Bulldogs (3-6, 2-5) had 350 yards of total offense. Key stats: IR-Fleming 3-129 TD receiving; Poittilo 9-20-1-188, TD passing, 4-19, TD rushing; Darrin Stephenson 8-38 rushing, INT, fumble recovery. KF-Michael Mason 9-120 receiving; Donte Long 16-88 rushing, INT; Sha'ka Miller 12-31-1-186 passing, 2 TDs rushing. - Reported by Scott Baxter Cox 35, Princess Anne 0 VIRGINIA BEACH - Chris Keller ran for two touchdowns, and the Falcons (2-7) scored 28 second-quarter points in winning a Beach District game and ending a three-game skid. Cox marched 72 yards on 10 plays, capped by Troy Ruediger's 13-yard touchdown run to take a 7-0 lead with 4:11 left in the first quarter. After Keller scored on a 4-yard run with 11:50 left in the half, King Saunders scored on a 24-yard interception return on the next play from scrimmage by Princess Anne (0-9). Zeke Novak added a 6-yard touchdown run, and Keller scored on a 29-yard carry to complete the scoring. Key stats: C-Keller 9-90, 2 TDs rushing; Ruediger 5-11-0-105 passing. - Reported by Trey Herbert Booker T. Washington 21, Granby 12 NORFOLK - Courtney Croom's 28-yard TD run in the fourth quarter allowed the Bookers (2-7, 2-4) to pull away for an Eastern District triumph. Granby (1-8, 1-5) pulled to 15-12 with five minutes left in the third quarter when Breon Corbett ran 79 yards for a TD. Key stats: G-Corbett, 3-81, 2 TDs rushing, 1-82 receiving; Joe Meeks, 3-11-2-140, TD passing; BTW-Eric Tyson, 9-91 rushing; Croom 7-56, 2 TDs rushing; James Vann 8-74 rushing. - Reported by Dan Moore Norcom 31, Wilson 0 PORTSMOUTH - Norcom (3-6, 3-3 Eastern District) turned three Wilson fumbles, an interception and a blocked punt into five touchdowns. The hard-luck Presidents (0-9, 0-6) had two 65-plus-yard touchdown runs nullified by penalties. Key stats: W-Tevis Gamble 15-87 rushing. N-Anthony Hines 10-59, 2 TDs rushing; Anthony Blount 6-45, TD rushing. - Reported by Bill Leffler Woodberry Forest 35, Norfolk Academy 7 WOODBERRY - Danny Martinez caught two touchdown passes and Femi Oyalowo ran for two TDs as the Tigers (4-4) avenged last season's loss by handing the Bulldogs their third consecutive defeat. Despite its late-season skid, Norfolk Academy (6-3) still figures to get a spot in the VIS Division I playoffs, which start next weekend. Key stats: WF-Oyalowo 29-195, 2 TDs rushing; Martinez 3-60, 2 TDs receiving; NA-Blake Rascoe 15-82 rushing. Greenbrier Christian 14, Isle of Wight Academy 8 CHESAPEAKE - Kelvin Howard's fourth-quarter interception rallied the Gators (3-6) past the Chargers, who came into the game ranked No. 1 in VIS Division III. With the Chargers (8-2) leading 8-6, Howard's interception led to a nine-play drive capped by Michael Johnson's 5-yard TD run with 4:27 left. Key stats: GCA-Josh Healey 16-28-1-177, TD passing; 19-79 rushing. IOW-Lance Moore 7-36 rushing. - Reported by Jerome Langston Hampton Roads Acad. 19, Nansemond-Suffolk 16 NEWPORT NEWS - The Saints (2-8, 2-2) lost two fumbles and had three passes intercepted in dropping a Tidewater Conference game to the Navigators (6-2, 3-1) in the teams' season finale. Jake Cochran had a fumble recovery and an interception, and Ben Kauder had two fourth-quarter interceptions for Hampton Roads Academy. The Navigators led 19-7 with a minute left in the third quarter before Daniel Raman tackled Walter Abruzzese for a safety, then J.R. Crowder scored on a 1-yard touchdown run to narrow the final score. Key stats: NSA-Tyler Van Selow, 27-135, TD rushing. HRA-Abruzzese 20-143, TD rushing. - Reported by Ryan Earley Norfolk Christian 43, Kenston Forest 22 BLACKSTONE - The Ambassadors (2-6) won their season finale behind Michael Booker's 105 rushing yards and two touchdown runs. Kenston Forest (2-8) pulled to 28-22 with nine minutes to play, but Norfolk Christian scored on its next two possessions to put the victory away. Key stats: NC-Booker, 16-105 2 TDs rushing, David Colonna 16-30, 2 TDs rushing, 3-7-0-144, 2 TD passing. - Reported by Gary Owens TODAY'S GAMES Staff writers Jami Frankenberry and Larry Rubama take a look at today's games: Nativity of Pennsylvania at Bishop Sullivan Catholic Time: 2 p.m. Records: Nativity 6-3, Bishop Sullivan 3-7 The lowdown: The Crusaders finish their season against a team from Pottsville that next week plays in the Class A playoffs for Pennsylvania's smallest schools. Jami says: Nativity, 35-13. Larry says: Nativity, 33-20. Arcadia at Atlantic Shores Time: 2 p.m. Records: Arcadia 1-7, Atlantic Shores 2-6 The lowdown: The past two meetings in this public school-private school battle have been high scoring. Atlantic Shores won last year 58-26 and 49-28 in 2004. Atlantic Shores has lost its past five games - four by 23 points or more. This is the Seahawks' second game against a Group A team this season after losing 47-12 to Nandua. Jami says: Atlantic Shores, 27-24. Larry says: Atlantic Shores, 31-23. Also: Chincoteague (2-5) at Broadwater Academy (6-2), 1:30 p.m. Jami says: Broadwater Academy, 26-12. Larry says: Broadwater Academy, 41-33. Smithfield (7-1 overall, 6-1 Bay Rivers District) at Tabb (5-3, 5-2), 7:30 p.m. Jami says: Smithfield, 28-19. Larry says: Smithfield, 37-26.

No. 3 Western Branch at Nansemond River Records: Western Branch 7-1 overall, 5-1 Southeastern District; Nansemond River 2-7, 1-6 The lowdown: Western Branch is in the thick of the Division 6 playoff race and needs a victory to set up a regular-season finale showdown against rival Deep Creek. The Bruins have won four in a row - all by 12 points or less - since losing to Oscar Smith. The Bruins rank sixth in South Hampton Roads in total defense, yielding an average of 169.2 yards per game. Nansemond River is playing in its season finale, and the Warriors have never defeated Western Branch. The teams began playing when Nansemond River moved to Group AAA in 1996. Warriors RB Jamar Jarrell has rushed for 631 yards, and WR Darryl Freeney leads the Southeastern District in scoring with 48 points (7 TDs, three 2-point conversions). Jami says: Tune-up time. Western Branch, 30-12. Larry says: Bruins roll as they prepare for the Creek. Western Branch, 33-15. Great Bridge vs. No. 4 Maury Site: Powhatan Field Records: Great Bridge 3-5, Maury 7-1 The lowdown: Maury has won the past two meetings in this non-district series, including 49-35 last season. Great Bridge has lost three of its past four games, but all three losses are by six points or less. The Wildcats fell 24-21 last week to Deep Creek. Great Bridge QB Casey Turner continues to fly up the all-time passing charts, and he's 8 yards from moving into fifth in career yards in South Hampton Roads. Three of Turner's targets - David Reynolds, Austin Taylor and Chris Stewart - are in the top five this season in receiving. Maury, riding a seven-game winning streak, appears headed for its first outright Eastern District title since 1990, with only one-win Granby remaining on the schedule. QB Stephen Kelley is 93 yards from his second consecutive 1,000-yard passing season. He threw for 1,274 yards last season at Indian River. Jami says: Commodores haven't played a .500 team since September. Maury, 38-24. Larry says: Maury hasn't seen a quarterback like this. Great Bridge, 37-34. No. 6 Deep Creek at Lakeland Records: Deep Creek 7-1 overall, 5-1 Southeastern District; Lakeland 1-7, 0-6 The lowdown: Deep Creek kept its playoff hopes alive by slipping past Great Bridge 24-21 last week. The Hornets have won four games by a TD or less. Lakeland snapped a 17-game losing streak with last week's 9-6 victory over Norcom. The Cavaliers haven't defeated Deep Creek since moving to Group AAA in 1996 and have scored nine total points in the teams' past two meetings. Jami says: Hornets can't wait for Western Branch. Deep Creek, 35-7. Larry says: Lakeland's one-game winning streak comes to an end. Deep Creek, 34-13. Green Run at No. 9 Landstown Records: Green Run 1-8 overall and Beach District, Landstown 6-2 The lowdown: Green Run enters its season finale on a five-game losing streak, and the Stallions never have defeated Landstown, which opened in 2001. Green Run WR Ronnie Dozier has 23 catches and is averaging 19.2 yards per reception. Landstown aims to keep its Division 6 playoff hopes alive and finishes the regular season next week against Bayside. The Eagles are coming off a bye. Sophomore RB Sterlin Phifer has been overshadowed in the Beach by big-name backs at Kempsville and Salem, but Phifer has 762 yards and six TDs. Jami says: Eagles won't be caught looking ahead. Landstown, 38-14. Larry says: Eagles keep playoff hopes alive. Landstown, 33-27. Ocean Lakes at No. 10 Kellam Records: Ocean Lakes 3-5 overall and Beach District, Kellam 6-2 The lowdown: Kellam needs to finish with victories today and next week against unbeaten Salem to keep its playoff hopes alive. The Knights, winner of three consecutive games, have the Beach District's top rushing offense, led by Javon Boddie's 685 yards. Kellam has won three straight games against Ocean Lakes. The Dolphins have lost back-to-back games and five of their past six. QB/RB/WR Marcus Davis caught six passes last Friday for 57 yards after rushing for 116 yards two weeks ago. Jami says: Knights need this one more. Kellam, 24-14. Larry says: Ocean Lakes' streak of 11 consecutive better-than-.500 seasons comes to an end. Kellam, 34-23. King's Fork at Indian River Records: King's Fork 3-5 overall, 2-4 Southeastern District; Indian River 4-4, 3-3 The lowdown: King's Fork was one quarter from pulling off a shocker last Friday but let a lead slip away against unbeaten Oscar Smith. The Bulldogs, playing in their third season, have been outscored 118-6 in two previous meetings with Indian River. The Braves have slipped out of playoff contention, but all of their losses are by 17 points or less. Sophomore QB Dravon Poittilo has thrown for 1,253 yards and 11 TDs. Jami says: Be careful, Braves. Indian River, 23-20. Larry says: King's Fork a pushover no more. Indian River, 27-20. Princess Anne at Cox Records: Princess Anne 0-8 overall and Beach District, Cox 1-7 The lowdown: Princess Anne, which finishes next week against Ocean Lakes, appears headed to its first winless season since 1988. The Cavaliers have lost 13 consecutive games and last finished better than .500 in 2000. Cox has lost three consecutive games, scoring two TDs in that span. Drew Jarrett has six FGs, tying him with Kempsville's Sean Teufel for the Beach District lead. Jami says: This one might be tough to watch. Cox, 9-6. Larry says: Princess Anne has been outscored 291-43 this season. Cox, 33-18. Bayside at First Colonial Records: Bayside 5-3 overall and Beach District, First Colonial 4-4 The lowdown: Bayside is coming off a 27-6 loss to Salem - a loss that doomed the Marlins' playoff hopes. QB E.J. Manuel was held to a season-low 91 yards, but he's 316 yards from breaking into South Hampton Roads' top-10 list of all-time passers. WR Jamal Johnson is one catch behind Great Bridge's David Reynolds for the South Hampton Roads receiving lead. Johnson has averaged 13.4 yards on his 43 catches. First Colonial RB Tony Gregory has 641 yards and seven TDs. He returned a kickoff 85 yards for a TD in last Friday's victory over Green Run. Jami says: Bayside, 27-22. Larry says: Bayside 37-27. Wilson at Norcom Records: Wilson 0-8 overall, 0-5 Eastern District; Norcom 2-6, 2-3 The lowdown: Wilson has lost 18 consecutive games, and last week's 24-0 loss to previously winless Granby was the Presidents' fifth by shutout this season. Norcom fell to Lakeland 9-6 last week, snapping the Cavaliers' 17-game skid. The Greyhounds have lost three of their past four games and are headed for their fourth consecutive losing season. With 844 yards, QB Cameron White is second in the Eastern District in passing. Jami says: Norcom, 23-0. Larry says: Norcom, 14-0. Granby at Booker T. Washington Records: Granby 1-7 overall, 1-4 Eastern District; Booker T. Washington 1-7, 1-4 The lowdown: Granby is coming off its first victory, 24-0 over Wilson, halting a nine-game losing streak. The Comets had scored seven total points in their previous three games. The Bookers have lost four in a row but played Lake Taylor tough before losing 20-14 last week. Jami says: Booker T. Washington, 23-14. Larry says: Booker T. Washington, 19-16. Norfolk Academy at Woodberry Forest Time: 3 p.m. Records: Norfolk Academy 6-2, Woodberry Forest 3-4 The lowdown: The Bulldogs slipped into a tie for second with Flint Hill in the VIS Division I rankings after last week's blowout loss to No. 1 Collegiate of Richmond. The Bulldogs still figure to make postseason play for the first time since 1997. Woodberry Forest lost 27-21 to Norfolk Academy last season, ending the Tigers' seven-game winning streak in the series. Woodberry Forest RB Femi Oyalowo has rushed for 365 yards in the past three games. Jami says: Norfolk Academy, 28-20. Larry says: Norfolk Academy, 33-24. Nansemond-Suffolk at Hampton Roads Academy Records: Nansemond-Suffolk Academy 2-7 overall, 2-1 Tidewater Conference; Hampton Roads Academy 5-2, 2-1 The lowdown: Both teams play their season finale in a game that will decide second place in the TCIS. Nansemond-Suffolk lost 35-0 last week against Blue Ridge. The Saints have dominated the series, winning each of the past five meetings, including 46-14 last season. Jami says: Hampton Roads, 22-21. Larry says: Hampton Roads, 27-23. Isle of Wight Academy at Greenbrier Christian Records: Isle of Wight Academy 8-1, Greenbrier Christian 2-6 The lowdown: Isle of Wight Academy, a defending private school state champion, is the top-ranked team in VIS Division III and steps up a level to face the Division II Gators. The Chargers won this match-up 48-25 last season. Isle of Wight Academy figures to host a state semifinal next week. The Chargers have split back-to-back one-point games, squeaking past rival Southampton Academy 22-21 last week. Jami says: Isle of Wight, 34-20. Larry says: Isle of Wight, 41-24. Norfolk Christian at Kenston Forest Records: Norfolk Christian 1-6, Kenston Forest 2-7 The lowdown: Norfolk Christian finishes its second season of football with a visit to Blackstone. The Ambassadors lost to Kenston Forest 35-23 last season. Jami says: Kenston Forest, 29-19. Larry says: Kenston Forest, 27-17. Franklin at Sussex Central Records: Franklin 6-2 overall, 2-0 Tri-Rivers District; Sussex Central 6-2, 2-0 The lowdown: This rivalry figures again to decide the Tri-Rivers District champion. Sussex Central has won six straight games since season-opening losses to William Campbell and Essex. Both Franklin and Sussex Central gave up 54 points in losses to Essex. Jami says: Sussex Central, 20-19. Larry says: Sussex Central, 27-22. Also: Blessed Sacrament Huguenot (6-4) at Southampton Academy (7-2), 7:30 p.m. Jami says: Southampton Academy, 32-28. Larry says: Southampton Academy, 37-23. New Kent (3-5 overall, 3-4 Bay Rivers District) at Southampton (6-2, 5-2), 7:30 p.m. Jami says: Southampton, 30-20. Larry says: Southampton, 38-23.

text: VirginianPilot-Whethe "Mission: Impossible III" (audio: ****, video: ****, extras: ****) the hyperkinetic thriller and the best of the franchise, is available in all three digital formats (DVD, HD-DVD, Blu-ray) in a two-disc collector's set. The high-def versions are clearly superior - especially the destructive missile attack on the Chesapeake Bay Bridge-Tunnel. The action sequence is mostly CGI, filmed on a makeshift bridge north of Los Angeles by TV wonder boy director J.J. Abrams ("Lost," "Alias"). Short bursts of aerial photography highlight the Chesapeake Bay as Cruise and the IMF agents escort his toughest villain, Philip Seymour Hoffman (Owen Davian), back to headquarters. Davian escapes, kidnapping Hunt's beautiful bride, Julia (Michelle Monaghan), to create more mayhem. The HD-DVD version includes a pop-up video commentary (small window over the flick) with Cruise and Abrams. It's so informative, the duo actually stop the movie a couple of times so they can breakdown a scene more thoroughly. Also, four documentaries were taped in HD, chronicling the production in Rome, United States and China, watchable in high-def with the HD-DVD and Blu-ray discs. (HD widescreen and enhanced widescreen, 2006, PG-13 for intense sequences of frenetic violence and menace, disturbing images and some sensuality) Inline image:VirginianPilot-Whethe Also, the complete "Mission Impossible: Ultimate Collection" is now available in HD-DVD and Blu-ray box sets. "Mission: Impossible" (audio: ****, video: ****, extras: **1/2) from director Brian De Palma was filmed mostly in historic Prague, Czech Republic. It features a much younger Cruise and Jon Voight as deceptive team leader Jim Phelps. The disc includes half-dozen documentaries, also found on the DVD released in April. Two highlight Cruise's 20-plus-year career, including his acceptance speech at last year's MTV Movie Awards with fiancee Katie Homes at his side. You guessed it; the two were like giggling teenagers at the promo. (HD widescreen, 1996, PG-13 for intense action violence) "Mission: Impossible II" (audio: ****, video: ***, extras: ***) doesn't fair as well in HD, exposing excess film grain and contrast outlines. Clearly, this tale steals a few pages from Hitchcock's classic "Notorious," with Cruise playing Cary Grant's role and Thandie Newton as Ingrid Bergman recruited to spy on her ex-lover. WASHINGTON, Va. - Sunday-afternoon casual in their ball caps, dungarees and open-collared shirts, the crowd in Ben "Cooter" Jones' front yard munched fried chicken and fresh-baked cake brought over by his neighbors in the Blue Ridge foothills. About 300 farmers, teachers, mechanics, shopkeepers and lots of retirees were enjoying some early October sunshine and the rollicking country music of "Cooter's Garage Band." As Democratic rallies go in Virginia's Republican heartland, it was "alarmingly large," joked John Fry, a former Democratic chairman in Fauquier County. When the guest of honor, U.S. Senate candidate Jim Webb, arrived, a few folks drifted over to shake his hand, but most kept their distance. Later, as he spoke, the applause was respectful but not always enthusiastic. "I see people who I know are Republicans," said Jones' wife, Alma Viatour. Many of them probably wouldn't have come to this Democratic rally without an invite from her husband, former TV co-star of "The Dukes of Hazzard," Viatour acknowledged. But their presence spoke to unease about a faraway war, their political party's course and curiosity about Webb, not long ago a Republican himself. "They don't like what's been going on," Viatour said. "They don't want to vote for the other guy." As Webb's neck-and-neck contest with U.S. Sen. George Allen moves into its final days, its success might depend on the candidate's appeal to thousands of voters in rural enclaves such as "Little Washington," which claims to be the first town named for America's first president. At 60, Webb has a lot in common with the voters he think s he needs. He grew up a Democrat, left the party when it turned against the Vietnam War, embraced the GOP in the Ronald Reagan era, and now - angry about the war in Iraq and Bush administration economic polices - is a Democrat reborn. "If the Reagan Democrats will come home, both parties are going to change," he said. Webb's journey from Democrat to Republican and back is a complicated tale of a complex man. It is the story of a war hero who became an outspoken war skeptic, a rebel who thrived in the notoriously regimented U.S. Naval Academy and the Marine Corps, and a man of action who became wealthy writing books. Webb's political hero, Andrew Jackson, may be a good place to start the story. President from 1829 to 1837, "Old Hickory" was the first chief executive from the Appalachian hills that were the nation's western frontier. He was proudly unrefined, a populist champion of farmers and backwoodsmen and a foe of the bankers and aristocrats who had held sway in politics since the revolution. "Andrew Jackson was an original," Webb wrote in "Born Fighting," his latest book, "an unusual and fearless leader." Jackson, who grew up an orphan in the Carolina hills, was the product of a Scots-Irish culture that migrated to America and took root in the Appalachians. The Scots-Irish revere military service, self-reliance and religious faith; they despise pretense and privilege. The same culture more than a century later produced Jim Webb. Webb grew up in military towns across the country and lives today with his wife, Hong Le Webb, in the comfortable Washington suburb of Falls Church. H e claims a sort of psychic home in such places as Gate City, Alley Hollow and Big Moccasin Gap in the Virginia mountains, where some of his kin still reside. In "Born Fighting," Webb described "this culture's unbending individualism - and its ingrained hatred of aristocracy." The Scots-Irish culture "has been in conflict with a variety of authoritarian power structures, and it remains so in today's America," he wrote. Published in 2004, the book is Webb's homage to his heritage, a defense of a group he say s was indispensable to the nation's development and has been ignored, or worse, by historians and intellectuals. "They came with nothing, and for a complicated set of reasons, many of them still have nothing," he wrote. "The slurs stick to me. Rednecks. Trailer-park trash. Racists. Cannon fodder. My ancestors. My people. Me." Like Jackson, Webb came to prominence as a military man. The son of an Air Force officer, Webb grew up in military towns. He remembers being "fiercely independent" as a child and often at loggerheads with his parents. James Webb taught James Jr. to hunt and fish and love the outdoors - and introduced him to poetry. His father refused to sign permission slips when teenage Jim wanted to take up organized boxing; his mother, Vera Hodges Webb, signed instead. The elder Webb later joked that he was responsible for his son's success because young Jim rejected every piece of advice he offered. Still, there was never any question in the son's mind that he would follow his dad into the military. Webb said his grades were mediocre but he scored well on standardized tests and "talked my way into" a Navy ROTC scholarship at the University of Southern California. His freshman-year academics were strong enough to win admission to the Naval Academy in 1964. "Jim was a gung-ho guy from the beginning," said Annapolis classmate and retired Marine Lt. Gen. Chip Gregson. Webb did well in class, particularly courses dealing with leadership, and as he had in high school, he pursued boxing. In his junior year, he fought for the brigade championship against another midshipman who would eventually go into politics: Oliver North. North was less experienced and stylistically inferior to Webb but narrowly won the fight on aggressiveness, author Robert Timberg wrote in "The Nightingale's Song," a 1995 book about Webb, North and three other prominent Annapolis graduates. The two men were seen as rivals during most of their time at Annapolis, friends say. The fight's outcome still is disputed in some quarters. "Nobody likes to lose.. I'm very competitive," Webb said. The Senate seat he now seeks is the one North failed to win when he ran as a Republican in 1996. That is only a coincidence, Webb said. By Webb's final year at Annapolis, as he and other midshipmen were choosing between the Navy and the Marines, much of the Class of 1968 reconsidered plans to enter the Corps. The Vietnam War was escalating, and the list of Academy grads killed or maimed seemed to grow each week. While the class failed to meet its Marine quota, Webb remained "a Marine through and through," said retired Navy Capt. Gordon Peterson, another classmate. Commissioned as a second lieutenant, Webb graduated first in his class at the Corps' basic school at Quantico and arrived in South Vietnam in March 1969. "He was just a natural as a platoon leader," said retired Marine Col. Mike Wyly, Webb's company commander in Vietnam. Wyly's custom was to send newcomers on night patrols. Hours after arriving at An Hoa, Webb was leading a squad into the darkness. The Marines encountered a larger group of North Vietnamese troops. Back at his command post, Wyly saw muzzle flashes, heard weapons firing, and figured Webb was a goner. But Webb called in artillery and air support, and in short order reported the enemy on the run and his squad unscathed. "I realized I had a guy with an awful lot of talent," Wyly said. By the time Webb's tour ended 13 months later, he had earned two Purple Hearts, a pair of Bronze Stars, the Silver Star and the Navy Cross, the second-highest award for valor in the U.S. military. Webb earned the Cross in July 1969 when members of his company, including Wyly, stumbled into a group of enemy bunkers while searching for weapons. "They were surrounded by us and we were surrounded by them," Wyly said. "They were surprised that this happened, and I was surprised that this happened." As Webb approached a bunker, three enemy fighters emerged. Webb grabbed the first and other two surrendered. Webb detonated a mine at the opening of a second bunker, and then ventured inside and seized what his medal citation described as "numerous documents containing valuable intelligence data." When the Marines moved to a third bunker, enemy troops rolled a grenade into their path; Webb rushed forward, firing at the enemy and using his body to shield his companions. Webb took shrapnel in his back and knee and "probably saved my life and a lot of other people's lives," said Wyly, who spent 34 years in the Marines. "I can't say that I saw anything more heroic." Webb's Vietnam tour ended whatever boyhood was left after Annapolis. "I was older when I was 24 than I am now," he tells interviewers. Recovered from his wounds, he hoped to command Marines in battle again. But the shrapnel so damaged his knee that the Corps moved him to a desk job at the Pentagon, where his bosses included future Sen. John Warner, then an assistant secretary of the Navy. Webb stayed for two years before leaving, frustrated at being away from the field, then left the Corps for Georgetown University law school in 1972. Webb said he was stunned to find a student culture that opposed the war and was contemptuous of those who fought it. His time at Georgetown stoked a rage that Webb said didn't dissipate until Sept. 11, 2001. "The strategy of the war deserved no prizes," Webb says today. He had no quarrel with those who opposed U.S. involvement in Vietnam. "I only had a problem when they turned on the people who served." A classmate urged him to support fellow Annapolis man Jimmy Carter in the 1976 presidential election, but Timberg writes that Webb was repulsed by Carter's plan to grant amnesty to Vietnam War-era draft evaders. He migrated to the GOP. Webb said he was particularly attracted to Ronald Reagan. He later served Reagan in the 1980s as assistant secretary of defense for reserve affairs and then secretary of the Navy. He quit the secretary post after 10 months in 1987 after disagreeing with Navy cutbacks. By the mid-1970s, Webb had begun writing, mostly articles for military journals. "Writing has probably defined me more than any other thing that I've done," he said recently. In 1979, he caused a stir - one that still reverberates today in his Senate campaign - with a Washingtonian magazine article titled "Women Can't Fight." It reflected his belief that the admission of women into the Naval Academy diminished the school's preparation of combat leaders. The article also highlighted his view that leaders were putting political correctness ahead of national defense. Webb has apologized repeatedly this year for much of the article's language, particularly his assertion that the mostly male brigade was "a horny woman's dream." But he has never completely backed away from its central argument - that the Academy produced better combat leaders when it was all-male. A year before Webb wrote the controversial article, he published his first novel. He struggled through seven full drafts of a Vietnam novel, "Fields of Fire." The book was rejected by 13 printing houses before being published by Prentice-Hall in 1978 to critical acclaim. Webb has since written five more novels, all with military themes, as well as several screenplays. "Fields of Fire" stands as his biggest success. The book is an unflinching account of the daily horror of battle, told from the viewpoint of the men who fought it. "It was a way for me to assimilate that experience, to put it in the right place in my life," Webb said. A key character in the book is Will Goodrich, who leaves Harvard to become a Marine. He loses a leg in battle and returns to college, then is shattered to find himself branded a killer by rich kids who'd ducked the draft. The book ends with Goodrich speaking at an antiwar rally and turning on his classmates. Webb put the scolding in capital letters. "HOW MANY OF YOU ARE GOING TO GET HURT IN VIETNAM? I DIDN'T SEE ANY OF YOU IN VIETNAM. I SAW DUDES MAN. DUDES AND TRUCK DRIVERS AND COAL MINERS AND FARMERS. I DIDN'T SEE YOU. WHERE WERE YOU? " The book established Webb as an author and as a spokesman for Vietnam War vets. His advocacy led Webb in 1982 to a leadership role in developing the Vietnam Veterans Memorial on the National Mall - and a bitter public fight over its design. Webb saw the original proposal - a black granite wall inscribed with the names of war dead - as an insult to those who fought. At his insistence, a statue of three battle-weary troops was placed near the memorial's entrance with an inscription recognizing "the courage, sacrifice and devotion to duty and country" of Vietnam War vet s. Webb "always looked after his people," said Dale Wilson, a North Carolina businessman and former Marine who lost both legs and an arm while serving with Webb. Wilson is among the old comrades Webb still checks on, 37 years after their tour. In the mid-1990s, when Wilson was ill with a mysterious abdominal ailment, Webb arranged to have him brought to the Navy's medical center in Bethesda, Md., where specialists fixed a dangerous arterial blockage. Wilson said he couldn't have navigated the Navy bureaucracy without Webb. "Jim's always been there." Webb said, "I watched a generation of people I served with, and I saw what happened to them.. The majority of them have gotten screwed." For years, Webb's passion for military service was matched by contempt for people such as former President Clinton, who spent the Vietnam War years at toney schools and took pains to avoid the military. But when the terrorist attacks came Sept. 11, 2001, Webb said that, for him, the wall that separated those who protested the Vietnam War and those who fought it came down. Webb said he wants to put Vietnam aside and make alliances with those who share his concern about Iraq. "What's going on now is so much more important," he said. Clinton and his wife, New York Sen. Hillary Clinton, have campaigned for Webb this month. His objections to the current war are consistent with his long-held feelings about the compact between soldiers and their civilian leaders. During a 1990 speech at the Confederate Memorial at Arlington National Cemetery, Webb foreshadowed his opposition. "There are at least two lessons for us to take away from such a day of remembrance," Webb said at that ceremony. "The first is one our leaders should carry next to their breasts and contemplate every time they face a crisis.. It is simply this: You hold our soldiers' lives in sacred trust. When a citizen has sworn to obey you, and follow your judgment, and walk onto a battlefield to defend the interests you define as worthy of his blood, do not abuse that awesome power through careless policy, unclear objectives or inflexible leadership. "The second lesson regards those who have taken such an oath and who have honored the judgment of their leaders, often at great cost. Intellectual analyses of national policy are subject to constant re-evaluation by historians as the decades roll by, but duty is a constant, frozen in the context of the moment it was performed." Webb said he went to war willingly and was proud to serve, as his family has always done. He groomed his son to do the same, taking the boy to former battlefields around the world, including Afghanistan and Vietnam. James Robert Webb, now serving in Iraq, joined the Marines. On the campaign trail, Webb wears combat boots to honor his son but deflects queries about Jimmy Webb's whereabouts and welfare. "I can't talk about it," he said. The sometimes self-righteous tone of his writings, along with his battles over the Vietnam Veterans Memorial and the budget struggle that caused him to resign as Navy secretary, have led some to wonder whether Webb could manage the compromises that are part of Senate life. Retired Marine Maj. Gen. Terry Murray said Webb "would have some challenges" in the Senate. Murray is a Webb friend and Annapolis classmate who had served as the Corps' Senate liaison. Former Nebraska Sen. Bob Kerrey, who earned the Medal of Honor in Vietnam and helped persuade Webb to run, said the Democrat will come to Senate debates "knowing what he thinks ought to be done. " "Before you can find common ground, you have to know what you believe," said Kerrey. Through the years, Webb said, he think s his writings have had some impact on national security debates. In 2005, though, he concluded that the issues of economic fairness - his concern that many Americans are being left behind as the country advances - can be addressed only from inside government. In February, he became a candidate. "Today, we risk being cut away from our government, from our democracy," Webb told an Alexandria crowd last month. Republican "slash-and-burn politics. have too often obscured the real issues for America.. "In a democracy, we are the boss. And George Allen and George Bush work for us. And the more people they can scare away or turn away from politics, the fewer bosses they're having. They don't want participation. They want to just move along with the status quo, lining the pockets of their corporate friends, protecting their own, while YOUR job goes overseas and your kid goes to Iraq." The words were delivered with a passion Webb often seems to suppress on the campaign trail, and the Democratic audience whooped its approval. Webb, who early in his campaign wouldn't approach strangers for fear of invading their space, acknowledges that politicking hasn't come easily. "There's so much crap in politics," Webb said, and the "traditional methodology. is something I've never apprenticed for." "I think I know how to cooperate and I know how to work across party lines," he said, noting that he spent four years after law school as a staff lawyer in the House. If he wins, he said, "the people who put me there are going to get six years of really innovative thought and willingness to confront the status quo." And if not? After fathering four children - one with his first wife, Barbara Samorajczyk, and three with his second wife, JoAnn Krukar Webb, a former Army nurse who is campaigning for him - Webb is about to become a dad again. Hong Webb, a Vietnam native and securities lawyer he met in the 1990s and married last year, is pregnant and due to deliver in December. During his first time around, Webb was "a very engaged father" whose writing career gave him plenty of freedom to spend time with his family, said Amy Hogan, at 36 Webb's eldest child and now a mother of three. He was a disciplinarian, with "a famous look that can crack a rock," she said, but he also has humorous streak. It has been 21 years since Webb last became a father, but the prospect of night feedings and diaper changes is not at all intimidating, he insisted. "I still know who I am, and I still have a life." text: No. 1 Oscar Smith at King's Fork Records: Oscar Smith 7-0 overall, 5-0 Southeastern District; King's Fork 3-4, 2-3 The lowdown: Oscar Smith pounded previously unbeaten Deep Creek last week for its 31st consecutive regular-season victory. The Tigers haven't missed a beat with backup QB Phillip Sims, a freshman, subbing for an injured Dexter Merritt. Sims has thrown for 633 yards and 10 TDs in his three starts, and he's expected to be behind center tonight as Merritt's knee continues to heal. King's Fork has taken grand strides in its third season, winning three of its past four games. The Bulldogs' defense ranks among South Hampton Roads' top 10 in total defense and points allowed. Jami says: Make it 32. Oscar Smith, 35-7. Larry says: Can anyone give the Tigers a game? Oscar Smith, 31-0. No. 6 Deep Creek vs. Great Bridge Site: Colon L. Hall Stadium (behind Great Bridge Middle School) Records: Deep Creek 6-1 overall, 4-1 Southeastern District; Great Bridge 3-4, 2-4 The lowdown: Deep Creek is coming off its first shutout loss since 1993 - a 35-0 spanking by Oscar Smith. The Hornets totaled minus-10 rushing yards. Deep Creek has three victories by seven points or less. Great Bridge boasts South Hampton Roads' passing leader, QB Casey Turner, who has 1,802 yards and 15 TDs. Turner last week hit six receivers, including two who hadn't caught a pass this season. David Reynolds leads the Wildcats - and the Southeastern District - with 35 receptions for 490 yards. Great Bridge's biggest obstacle could be history. The Wildcats have lost 13 consecutive games in the series, a streak that dates to 1992. Jami says: It's about time. Great Bridge, 28-27. Larry says: But not tonight. Deep Creek, 34-28. The Lions' defense hasn't surrendered more than a touchdown since a 14-9 loss to Bayside in mid-September, and this is a tricky game since unbeaten Salem looms next week. Ocean Lakes' season has spiraled away, thanks mostly to injuries. The Dolphins have lost four of their past five games. Star RB Roy Banks is banged up and managed just 35 yards in last week's loss to Bayside. But do-everything junior Marcus Davis, who usually plays receiver but also plays some quarterback and returns kicks, rushed for 116 yards last Friday. Jami says: Can the Lions prove me wrong (again)? Washington 1-6, 1-3 The lowdown: Lake Taylor is coming off a bye and has won three consecutive games since a loss to Maury. The Titans are in good shape to make the Division 5 playoffs but need to win this one and finish with victories over Churchland and Norview. RB George McInnis leads Lake Taylor with 781 yards. Booker T. Washington has lost three straight and is headed for its worst season since going 2-8 in 2000. The Bookers had won four consecutive games against Lake Taylor before last year's 48-14 loss. Warriors RB Jamar Jarrell has 585 rushing yards and leads the Southeastern District. If he holds on, he'll be the first Suffolk player to lead the district in rushing since Nansemond River's Trayce McPherson in 2003. All three of Hickory's losses have been by a touchdown or less, but none has hurt more than last week's five-overtime defeat to Western Branch. That loss doomed the Hawks' playoff chances. Larry says: First Colonial, 26-20.
