text: "Fast Times at Ridgemont High" "Army of Darkness" Both films offer laughs, although each might appeal to different tastes. "Fast Times at Ridgemont High" follows a group of 80's-era high school students growing fast up in California. It's based on the book by Cameron Crowe, who wrote and directed "Jerry McQuire" and "Elizabethtown." Amy Hecklerling, the director/writer of "Clueless," directs here. Crowe and Heckerling pair up for commentary that tells us who else was in the running for lead roles. They also share plenty of Sean Penn stories. Penn, who played stoned surfer Jeff Spicoli, stayed so in character, he would only respond to "Jeff" on set and off. Commentary suggests that wasn't as much fun in real life as it sounds. But you might have heard all this before. Commentary and extras, good as they are, are no different from the Special Edition DVD released in 2004. As a matter of fact, you'll have to flip the HD disc to the standard DVD side to pick up the extras. "Army of Darkness" didn't even fare that well; a theatrical trailer is the lone extra. The "Director's Cut," released in 2000, contained terrific commentary from writer/director Sam "Spiderman" Raimi and the film's wonderfully weird star, Bruce Campbell. There was also 15 minutes of additional footage and an alternate ending. Even more extras can be found on the "Special Edition" released in 1999. So hang on to those jewels if you've got them. "Army of Darkness" is the third film in Raimi's "Evil Dead" series of low budget horror flicks and looks superb in HD. Campbell returns as chainsaw and shotgun wielding Ash, the valiant S-Mart clerk. Ash finds himself transported back to medieval times where, once again, he must battle the undead. But somehow the horror dissolves into a Three Stooges-rolled-into-one comedy fiasco complete with Ray Harryhousen-like effects. There's never been anything like "Army of Darkness" or Ash. (Both: HD widescreen. "Army of Darkness": 1993, rated R for violence and horror. "Fast Times at Ridgemont High": 1982, rated R for sex, nudity, language and drug use) Kay Reynolds The wonder teens of Newport, Calif., are back in "The O.C.: The Complete Third Season," (audio: ****, video: ***1/2, extras: ***) but not all of them will make it back for fourth-season premiere on Fox in November. If you didn't see the fantastical ending of season three, buy the box set, or at least borrow it to find out what happens. The season's begins with Kirsten in rehab, Marissa and Ryan and Seth and Summer all snuggly-wuggly, and Julie trying to make another go with ex-hubby, Jimmy. Of course, as each hour-episode unfolds, the couples' bliss is short-lived, and someone always is stirring the pot Kaitlin Cooper, Julie's daughter and Marissa's sister, for one. The special features on this seven-disc set are mostly worth watching, whether you're a teen or not. There's the hackneyed making-of video for "The Subways," performing at The Bait Shop, and there's a gag reel, where it's fun to watch Adam Brody (Seth) and Peter Gallagher (Sandy) mess up; they're funny guys. The real gems on this set include creator/writer Josh Schwartz and a pair of executive producers/writers actually using a remote control to scan through two episodes, "The Undertow" and "The Pot Stirrer." During "The Undertow," Schwartz explains how he demanded writer J.J. Philbin write sex scenes for each couple in the show. The two share laughs over that. In another feature, "The Party Favor: From Script to Screen," the viewer gets to see how episode No. 23 about prom is made from the screenplay writing to the editing room. Now we can see how the editor put together the big fight between Ryan and Volchok, and watch Summer's stunt-double take a fall for Rachel Bilson. The other great feature on disc five, "What's in a Name?", is also worth a look. Schwartz and others on the show tell how they've used people in their lives and stolen names for O.C. characters. The interviews with the people who get the "shout outs" on the show, those fleeting 15 minutes of fame, are funny and honest. (Enhanced widescreen, 2005-06, not rated) Toni Guagenti At 78 minutes, "Looking for Kitty" (audio: **1/2, video: **1/2, extras: **1/2), is yet another thin and unremarkable effort from writer/director/actor Edward Burns, who has made a career following the romantic troubles of sad sacks in New York City. "Kitty," which has been on the shelf for two years, was shot for $200 grand on digital video. It stars Burns as an incompetent private eye who agrees to help a high school baseball coach ("Numb3rs" star David Krumholtz) find his wife who has left him for a rock star. Burns contributes an intelligent commentary, sharing tidbits about the low budget production that should interest budding filmmakers. Also included is an alternate opening. Worth a rental only if you're a Burns fan. (Enhanced wide-screen, 2006, Rated R for language and some sexual references) Josh Boone Remember the theme song "They're creepy and they're kooky, mysterious and ooky. They're altogether spooky The Addams Family"? If you don't, you can join in the karaoke sing-along with Thing, found among the extras of "The Addams Family: Volume One" (audio: ***, video: ***, extras: ****). Twenty-two of the black and white episodes, based on the macabre cartoons of Charles Addams, are available on a 3-flip-disc set. It's nice to see how the creator is remembered here, particularly in the documentary, "You Rang, Mr. Addams?" Initially, Addams created cartoons around a variety of characters. Some the basis for Morticia, Gomez, Uncle Fester, Lurch, Wednesday and Pugsley began to appear again and again, falling into a ghoulish "family" motif. When Addams was approached by MGM to develop his work into a series, he had to finally name and describe them. Lisa Loring, Ken Weathermax and Felix Silla, who played Wednesday, Pugsley and Cousin Itt, provide commentary and interviews, along with Stephen Cox, author of "The Addams Chronicles." John Astin (Gomez) also shows up for interviews. Vic Mizzy, who wrote the memorable theme and other Addams' mood music, has his own featurette to tell us how he did it. Aside from the annoying flip-discs, this is a great presentation for a unique and well-loved family sit-com. (Fullscreen, black & white, 1964, not rated) Kay Reynolds - Sometimes you just have to buy an entire series on DVD in hopes that the extras will get better or be included on the discs; "Wings: The Complete Third Season" (audio: ***1/2, video: ***1/2, extras: 0) is one of those shows. This season brings Helen (Crystal Bernard) back to Nantucket to contend with Joe's new girlfriend. Of course, that can't last the entire season, so the viewer cheers Helen on, not only to get back with Joe, but to become the accomplished, recognized cellist she dreams of becoming. Oh, first, she has to marry Antonio (Tony Shalhoub). Laughs are abundant in all 22 season three episodes. "Wings" spawned some talented actors, including Shalhoub ("Monk"), Thomas Haden Church ("Sideways") and Tim Daly ("Sopranos"). They're out there, CBS Paramount, so go find them and get them to do special features, commentary, anything. We'll wait for subsequent seasons on DVD to see how that turns out. (Fullscreen, 1991-92, not rated) Toni Guagenti Can you say "parody"? Well if you can, "Greg the Bunny: Best of Film Parodies" (audio: ***, video: ***, extras: ***) is for you. The Independent Film Channel's cult favorite comes in a two-DVD set that contains 14 episodes of parodies of classic films such as, "Pulp Fiction," "Easy Rider" and "The Godfather" among others. Most of the approximately 15-minute episodes are funny and stand up well enough on their own. You needn't to have seen "Fargo" with its infamous woodchipper, or "Miller's Crossing" or even "Auto Focus" to enjoy "Sex, Button Eyes, and a Video Ape," which charts Greg's Bob Crane-like descent into homemade video porn addiction. But it does help to be well-versed in some form of "filmography" to FULLY enjoy what those crazy, perverse puppets Greg, Warren and Count Blah are serving up in this DVD set. Please note: This is not the Fox sitcom, which was cancelled before the show made its way to IFC. This is not for the family. Extras include commentaries on all 14 episodes by the show's creators; a "gag" reel; photo galleries; two featurettes and some deleted scenes. These parodies are out of the box. No strings attached. (Fullscreen, 1, not rated, Includes scenes of graphic violence, illegal drug use, nudity.and some puppet sex) Cliff Redding Politics and passion are the topics for two of Docurama's latest DVD offerings. Despite being released in 2004, both are timely but only one makes a real impact. The title subject in the surprisingly engaging "The Education of Shelby Knox: Sex, Lies and Education" (audio: ***1/2, video: ***, extras: 0), is an idealistic teen from Lubbock, Texas, a city that in 2002 had some of the highest rates of STDs in the country. Pledged to wait for sex until marriage by her church, she still bristles at the disconnect between the school district's abstinence-only policy and her pregnant classmates. With the wary support of her conservative parents, Knox joins the fledgling Lubbock Youth Commission in the hopes of winning an audience with the school board. (That's the Brooklyn neighborhood of Bedford-Stuyvesant, for those not up on New York lingo.) Comedian Chris Rock weaves tales from his childhood in New York in his sitcom "Everybody Hates Chris: The First Season" (audio: ***, video: ***, extras: ****). Tichina Arnold, Terry Crews, Imani Hakim and Tequan Richmond star. Tyler James Williams stars as Chris. Executive producer and co-creator Ali LeRoi shares the science of casting in the DVD extras. Williams, a fairly unknown actor before the show, was a perfect fit because the audience could get to know him as Chris. Better than that, Williams was a real 13-year-old boy, awkwardness and all. Hakim, a Cleveland native, makes the perfect little sister because she looks like an ordinary neighborhood kid. "I was happy because I came out of the ghetto and got this part," Hakim says in the extras. And Richmond just has that cooler younger brother look, Rock and LeRoi said. The comedy is loosely based on Rock's life, but it's no autobiography. Rock really has six brothers and one sister. On the show, he has two siblings. "There's a portion of the show that reflects Chris' life, and it's really in the tone," LeRoi said. Bradley Although the Mormon Church banned polygamy in 1890, at least 40,000 people are thought to practice it and more may be watching it on cable. HBO continues its tradition of delivering the finest dramatic shows on television with "Big Love: The Complete First Season" (audio: ***1/2, video: ***1/2, extras: **1/2), an even-handed look at modern-day polygamy in Salt Lake City. Bill Paxton stars as the head of the family with three beautiful wives (Jeanne Tripplehorn, Chloe Sevigny, Ginnifer Goodwin), seven kids, and a thriving business. He has all the trouble three families would bring three mortgages, warring personalities, sexual dysfunction, and more. Harry Dean Stanton steals the show as the creepy backwoods patriarch of a polygamist commune. As is always the case with HBO, this five-disc set containing 12 episodes will run you a very steep $100. Extras are also thin for a set this highly priced. Three commentaries and a brief look at the creation of the opening title sequence are all viewers have to chew on. But if you want the best, you have to pay the price. (Enhanced wide-screen, 2006, unrated) - Josh Boone Eloise is an imp with a heart and her personality shines through on IDT Entertainment's new line of animated stories, including the new releases "Me, Eloise" and "Eloise: Little Miss Christmas" (both: audio: ***, video: ***, extras: ***). Staying true to the character's precociousness, the creators have made up great storylines that show Eloise's curious, creative personality and her ability to be inclusive and generous. In the first show, Eloise makes friends with an 8-year-old violin prodigy from Tokyo who moves into New York's famous Plaza Hotel. Eloise teaches Yuko and her parents that there is more to life than practicing the violin. In the Christmas show, Eloise and her Plaza pals go to great lengths in the face of many roadblocks to put on a yuletide show for some of New York's downtrodden. New characters are introduced, but they stay true to the fun and antics. Lynn Redgrave voices Nanny, Eloise's guardian when her mother's not around, and Tim Curry voices Plaza manager Mr. Salamone; both do fabulous jobs in those roles. The extras are quite fun, too. The menu is an elevator, and viewers push the floor buttons to access special features, including cartoon shorts and Plaza scenes. Other extras include a quick look at some of the shows' characters as narrated by Eloise, a different game on each of the DVDs and a look at sketches and the final animated product that run simultaneously on the screen it's pretty neat. Eloise creator Kay Thompson is rumored to have based her books on her own life, as well as that of her goddaughter, Liza Minelli and she would probably get a kick out of this version of her famous creation. (Both: Enhanced widescreen and fullscreen, 2006, not rated) - Toni Guagenti The bonus, in and of itself, is owning "It's The Great Pumpkin, Charlie Brown" (audio: ****, video, ****, extras: *) on DVD. So don't get excited, because that story and a bonus feature, "You're Not Elected, Charlie Brown," are all you get on this "Peanuts Classic" release. Watching Sally, Charlie Brown's sister, freak out on Linus after they miss Halloween camped out in the pumpkin patch waiting for the Great Pumpkin is hysterical. "You blockhead!" she screams at him, realizing she's missed out on the candy-collecting. Plus, she can't get any goodies from her brother, because all he got was rocks. This classic can be enjoyed over and over again. In the second feature, Charlie Brown doesn't get to run for class office because Lucy's unscientific polling discovers no one would vote for him. Poor Charlie Brown. But Linus gets a shot and almost blows it after promising the kids a visit from the Great Pumpkin as part of his platform. The colors pop on this DVD, including the vivid hues of Linus' red tee, Lucy's blue dress and Charlie Brown's yellow shirt. The music's in Dolby Digital, and Vince Guaraldi's score is perfect. (Fullscreen, 1966, not rated) Toni Guagenti Peter Bogdanovich's "They All Laughed: 25th Anniversary Edition" (audio: ***, video: ***, extras:***) features Audrey Hepburn in her final starring role in a theatrical film. Although both Quentin Tarantino and Wes Anderson consider it one of their favorite films of all time, it was a huge bomb when it was originally released and nearly destroyed Bogdanovich. Actress Dorothy Stratten was murdered after the film's shooting was completed and studios distanced themselves from the film, refusing to release it because of the bad publicity surrounding the tragedy. Bogdanovich put in $5 million of his own money and distributed the film himself. The shooting was also plagued by tension on the set between Hepburn and actor Ben Gazzara, who had recently split up with Hepburn to marry another woman. Twenty-five years have put enough distance between the behind-the-scenes drama to make it possible to appreciate this tremendously fun, if slight, screwball comedy about a team of detectives who get involved with two women they are investigating for suspected adultery. The DVD includes a video conversation between Bogdanovich and Anderson and a thoroughly enjoyable commentary by Bogdanovich. (Enhanced wide-screen, 1981, rated PG) - Josh Boone "Numb3rs: The Complete Second Season" (audio: ***, video: ***, extras: ***1/2) builds on the half-season that got the series off to a solid start. Forget struggles to de-randomize shooting sprees; mathematician Charlie Eppes (David Krumholtz) helps his brother Don (Rob Morrow) and other FBI agents solve arsons, stalkings and robberies this season. The set offers seven episodes with commentaries that run the gamut from lighthearted efforts that offer little insight ("Obsession") to discussions that provide a lot of technical information ("Scorched," which talks about how they set up and film the fiery effects) to one that tackles the sensitive issue of how the creators mixed the issue of gang murders with David Sinclair (Alimi Ballard) in "The O.G." That episode was problematic because the creators didn't want to link Sinclair, the show's key black agent, to gangs. He discusses his initial reaction to the episode and how his attitude changed after seeing the script and talking with the director. The other extras bloopers and two behind-the-scenes featurettes with Nicolas Falacci and Krumholtz aren't really worth viewing. (Enhanced widescreen, 2005-06, not rated but adult content for violence) L.A. Luebbert In "Combat Diary: The Marines of Lima Company" (audio: ***, video: ***, extras: ***) we get to see what it was like for one of the hardest-hit combat units in the war. Along with all their other gear, the Reserve unit from Columbus, Ohio, was equipped with home video cameras. This war documentary produced by A&E IndieFilms is raw. It is a firsthand account of what the real deal is in Iraq. The heat, the connection between the troops. The casualties. It is revealing to see the initial enthusiasm of the company and how that feeling changes as the reality of war sets in. For those who want to romanticize the war, it's not going to happen here. Wherever your political beliefs about the war in Iraq lie, watching this riveting DVD will show you another view from the vantage point of the warriors. Extras include bonus footage that was left out of the original offering. There is a very touching video greeting from a Marine who taped a birthday message to his daughter back home just a month before he was killed. There is also a slide show with commentary by three of the men who took the pictures and a biography/filmography of the director. (Enhanced widescreen, 2006, not rated but contains some very graphic material) Cliff Redding As "That 70s Show: Season Five" (audio: ***1/2, video: ***1/2, extras: **) gets rolling, Eric (Topher Grace), Donna (Laura Prepon), Kelso (Ashton Kutcher) and the gang are gearing up for their senior year of high school. For the series, much like many a star high-school athlete, it would be all downhill after that. But season five presents the cast and writing still in prime form and, arguably, at its peak of popularity. Guest appearances by Jessica Simpson and Luke Wilson, among others, help add spice to the goings-on. The set's weak lineup of extras continues an ongoing trend with this series. While the first couple of seasons feature some audio commentaries and other standard goodies, this set (and the previous two) includes a pair of rather weak featurettes sit-downs with Danny Masterson and Wilmer Valderrama as well as the original promos for each episode and "Season 5 in 5 Minutes," which offers a quick rundown of the season's main story arcs. These sets could be much more impressive if only Fox would put a little bit of pride into their work. (Fullscreen, 2002, not rated) Robert Hatfield In "Andy Milonakis: The Complete Second Season," (audio: ***, video: ***, extras: ****) the rapping Jewish kid from the Lower East Side only gets better. Part hidden-camera reality show, part sketch comedy and part, well, crazy, the MTV2 show thrives with a unique brand of comedy that's low-budget and childish think biting into a worm and finding an apple, or a tin-can phone that leaks creamed corn. This season Andy, who, because of a birth defect looks like a teenager but is in fact 30 years old, continues to terrorize old folks in the L.E.S and lampoon his dim-witted sidekick Ralphie. Fifteen extra skits are included each of them more silly and strange than the next as well as two music videos in which Andy does his cartoonish but surprisingly decent raps. Warning: This is only for the truly goofy it's like Tom Green drunk on soda. (Fullscreen, 2006, not rated) - Malcolm Venable When a TV show's title is too rude for print, it goes without saying that its content may be more than a little risque. The magician duo at the helm of "Penn & Teller: Bulls**t! The Complete Third Season" (audio: ***, video, ***, extras, no stars) certainly haven't run out of opinions to express or dubious claims to debunk. They are hostile to conspiracy theories, government intrusion, organized religion, self-help mumbo-jumbo, the paranormal and silly toupees which is to say, viewers never know whether they'll be entertained, offended, or both. In the raucous, profanity-laced third season, the Showtime show takes on hair obsessions, circumcision (you can imagine the visual aids employed), gun control, family values, life coaching, religious relics (such as the Virgin Mary grilled-cheese sandwich), the Endangered Species Act and America's relentless quest for the best. The show is sometimes cruel and bombastic, but so gleefully irreverent that it's hard to stay angry for long. How upset can you get with a show that dares to show exactly yes, exactly what a bikini wax entails? Although there's plenty to enjoy in the third season, there's nothing extra to cheer about on this three-disc set. The only goodies are a lame collection of publicity photos and a list of the duo's movie and TV credits no outtakes, extra footage or commentaries. Packaging three discs with no decent extras? As Penn Jillette would say, that's a load of well, you get the drift. (Fullscreen, 2005, not rated) Caroline Luzzatto Three minor Michael Caine films are out as part of 20th Century Fox's Cinema Classics Collection. The biggest disappointment is "The Magus" (audio: ***, video: ***, extras: **), based on John Fowles' bestselling novel. Fowles wrote the screenplay of this convoluted, pretentious movie, starring Caine as Nicholas, an English teacher assigned to a school on a little Greek island. When Nicholas meets an enigmatic character named Maurice (Anthony Quinn) who lives with a beautiful young woman (Candice Bergen), the weirdness begins. Meanwhile, Nicholas is involved in a troubled relationship with a stewardess (Anna Karina), who appears from time to time in flashbacks. What is actually going on in the story is anyone's guess. There are plays within plays, masquerades, hints of magic and insanity, replete with awkward, purple prose. The one extra on this disc is a somewhat interesting documentary on Fowles, containing interviews with his biographer, fans, a literature professor and his editor at Little, Brown. In discussing "The Magus," Fowles' first novel, which took him 10 years to write, the prof sees the themes as true love and the meaning of life. His editor calls him the "best prose stylist of the 20th century." (Enhanced wide screen, 1968, rated PG) In "Deadfall" (audio: ***, video: ***, extras: **1/2), Caine is a jewel thief who is sucked into an elaborate heist scheme with an unlikely married couple. There is enough going on in this (comparatively) well-written film to keep it interesting. One special feature offers the isolated score, composed by John Barry. There is also a documentary on Barry and his illustrious career. The English composer was responsible for the James Bond soundtracks, "Out of Africa," "Body Heat," "The Lion in Winter," and hundreds more. Barry has a bit part in "Deadfall" as the conductor of a beautiful guitar symphony he composed. (Enhanced wide screen, 1968, rated R for nudity and sexual situations) "Peeper" (audio: **, video: ***, extras: **) stars Caine as Leslie Tucker, an L.A. private eye in 1947, hired by an eccentric wealthy man to find his adult daughter, who had been adopted as a child, so he can give her her rightful inheritance. Tucker finds the right family but isn't sure which of the daughters (played by Natalie Wood and Kitty Winn) is the lucky one. This spoof of a film noir is mildly entertaining, but definitely a grade B-minus. Extras include an interview with the director, Peter Hyams, who confesses to being a "Raymond Chandler freak." Hyams refers to the box office failure of the film as one of the "scars" in his life. In another, much more enjoyable, extra, film noir is examined in general. Clips from classic '40s movies are shown, as are more modern ones from the "rebirth" of the genre, with examples like "Chinatown" and "Taxi Driver." (Enhanced widescreen, 1975, rated PG) Peggy Earle

Two documentaries featured on the low-tech DVD have vanished, one that highlighted Haskins' 30-year-plus career, the other that included interviews with his players and colleagues. Two commentaries are intact, including one with first-time director James Gartner, handpicked by producer Jerry Bruckheimer. Gartner is quite open about his shortcomings, wishing he had tightened a few scenes, but details the racial tension on-screen in scenes with Bobby Joe Hill (Derek Luke). "Luke's character is full of quiet anger, as benched talent," Gartner says, since most black players of his era never saw action in the South. (HD widescreen, 2006, PG for racial issues including violence and epithets, and momentary language) Samsung Blu-ray player update: The first firmware software download is available at () to correct issues that have plagued the player since its launch in June minus the fix for the slightly soft picture. That will be addressed in the next version. Here's the list of fixes with firmware 1.0v (DTS sound causing image jitter, improved loading time, correct analog outputs if reversed, and 4:3 pillarboxing for BD content) - Bill Kelley III Paul Weitz, the writer and director of "In Good Company," satirizes both "American Idol" and George Bush's presidency in "American Dreamz" (audio:***1/2, video:***1/2, extras:***), a film that succeeds as often as it fails. Hugh Grant plays the Simon Cowell-esque host, Mandy Moore plays the camera-loving idol, and Dennis Quaid plays the bumbling Bush clone who serves as guest judge on the "American Idol" stand-in "American Dreamz" to raise his falling numbers with voters. Weitz insists he wrote the script before ever watching "American Idol," something very hard to believe. Extras include a commentary with Weitz and actor Sam Golzari (who has the best role in the film as a sleeper cell terrorist who would rather dance and sing than kill anyone), deleted scenes, and two brief featurettes. (Enhanced wide-screen, 2006, rated PG-13 for brief strong language and some sexual references) Josh Boone Watch your back or get got. That was the way of life for some in Bed-Stuy in the '80s. (That's the Brooklyn neighborhood of Bedford-Stuyvesant, for those not up on New York lingo.) Comedian Chris Rock weaves tales from his childhood in New York in his sitcom "Everybody Hates Chris: The First Season" (audio: ***, video: ***, extras: ****). Tichina Arnold, Terry Crews, Imani Hakim and Tequan Richmond star. Tyler James Williams stars as Chris. Executive producer and co-creator Ali LeRoi shares the science of casting in the DVD extras. Williams, a fairly unknown actor before the show, was a perfect fit because the audience could get to know him as Chris. Better than that, Williams was a real 13-year-old boy, awkwardness and all. Hakim, a Cleveland native, makes the perfect little sister because she looks like an ordinary neighborhood kid. "I was happy because I came out of the ghetto and got this part," Hakim says in the extras. And Richmond just has that cooler younger brother look, Rock and LeRoi said. The comedy is loosely based on Rock's life, but it's no autobiography. Rock really has six brothers and one sister. On the show, he has two siblings. "There's a portion of the show that reflects Chris' life, and it's really in the tone," LeRoi said. The 22-episode DVD release also includes cast and crew commentaries on select episodes, featurettes, bloopers, deleted scenes, set photos and audition reels. It's comedy and Chris Rock is involved, so of course, it's lots of fun. (Enhanced widescreen, 2005-06. not rated) DeAnne M. Bradley Although the Mormon Church banned polygamy in 1890, at least 40,000 people are thought to practice it and more may be watching it on cable. HBO continues its tradition of delivering the finest dramatic shows on television with "Big Love: The Complete First Season" (audio: ***1/2, video: ***1/2, extras: **1/2), an even-handed look at modern-day polygamy in Salt Lake City. Bill Paxton stars as the head of the family with three beautiful wives (Jeanne Tripplehorn, Chloe Sevigny, Ginnifer Goodwin), seven kids, and a thriving business. He has all the trouble three families would bring three mortgages, warring personalities, sexual dysfunction, and more. Harry Dean Stanton steals the show as the creepy backwoods patriarch of a polygamist commune. As is always the case with HBO, this five-disc set containing 12 episodes will run you a very steep $100. Extras are also thin for a set this highly priced. Three commentaries and a brief look at the creation of the opening title sequence are all viewers have to chew on. But if you want the best, you have to pay the price. (Enhanced wide-screen, 2006, unrated) - Josh Boone Eloise is an imp with a heart and her personality shines through on IDT Entertainment's new line of animated stories, including the new releases "Me, Eloise" and "Eloise: Little Miss Christmas" (both: audio: ***, video: ***, extras: ***). Staying true to the character's precociousness, the creators have made up great storylines that show Eloise's curious, creative personality and her ability to be inclusive and generous. In the first show, Eloise makes friends with an 8-year-old violin prodigy from Tokyo who moves into New York's famous Plaza Hotel. Eloise teaches Yuko and her parents that there is more to life than practicing the violin. In the Christmas show, Eloise and her Plaza pals go to great lengths in the face of many roadblocks to put on a yuletide show for some of New York's downtrodden. New characters are introduced, but they stay true to the fun and antics. Lynn Redgrave voices Nanny, Eloise's guardian when her mother's not around, and Tim Curry voices Plaza manager Mr. Salamone; both do fabulous jobs in those roles. The extras are quite fun, too. The menu is an elevator, and viewers push the floor buttons to access special features, including cartoon shorts and Plaza scenes. Other extras include a quick look at some of the shows' characters as narrated by Eloise, a different game on each of the DVDs and a look at sketches and the final animated product that run simultaneously on the screen it's pretty neat. Eloise creator Kay Thompson is rumored to have based her books on her own life, as well as that of her goddaughter, Liza Minelli and she would probably get a kick out of this version of her famous creation. (Both: Enhanced widescreen and fullscreen, 2006, not rated) - Toni Guagenti The bonus, in and of itself, is owning "It's The Great Pumpkin, Charlie Brown" (audio: ****, video, ****, extras: *) on DVD. So don't get excited, because that story and a bonus feature, "You're Not Elected, Charlie Brown," are all you get on this "Peanuts Classic" release. Watching Sally, Charlie Brown's sister, freak out on Linus after they miss Halloween camped out in the pumpkin patch waiting for the Great Pumpkin is hysterical. "You blockhead!" she screams at him, realizing she's missed out on the candy-collecting. Plus, she can't get any goodies from her brother, because all he got was rocks. This classic can be enjoyed over and over again. In the second feature, Charlie Brown doesn't get to run for class office because Lucy's unscientific polling discovers no one would vote for him. Poor Charlie Brown. But Linus gets a shot and almost blows it after promising the kids a visit from the Great Pumpkin as part of his platform. The colors pop on this DVD, including the vivid hues of Linus' red tee, Lucy's blue dress and Charlie Brown's yellow shirt. The music's in Dolby Digital, and Vince Guaraldi's score is perfect. (Fullscreen, 1966, not rated) Toni Guagenti Peter Bogdanovich's "They All Laughed: 25th Anniversary Edition" (audio: ***, video: ***, extras:***) features Audrey Hepburn in her final starring role in a theatrical film. Although both Quentin Tarantino and Wes Anderson consider it one of their favorite films of all time, it was a huge bomb when it was originally released and nearly destroyed Bogdanovich. Actress Dorothy Stratten was murdered after the film's shooting was completed and studios distanced themselves from the film, refusing to release it because of the bad publicity surrounding the tragedy. Bogdanovich put in $5 million of his own money and distributed the film himself. The shooting was also plagued by tension on the set between Hepburn and actor Ben Gazzara, who had recently split up with Hepburn to marry another woman. Twenty-five years have put enough distance between the behind-the-scenes drama to make it possible to appreciate this tremendously fun, if slight, screwball comedy about a team of detectives who get involved with two women they are investigating for suspected adultery. The DVD includes a video conversation between Bogdanovich and Anderson and a thoroughly enjoyable commentary by Bogdanovich. (Enhanced wide-screen, 1981, rated PG) - Josh Boone "Numb3rs: The Complete Second Season" (audio: ***, video: ***, extras: ***1/2) builds on the half-season that got the series off to a solid start. Forget struggles to de-randomize shooting sprees; mathematician Charlie Eppes (David Krumholtz) helps his brother Don (Rob Morrow) and other FBI agents solve arsons, stalkings and robberies this season. The set offers seven episodes with commentaries that run the gamut from lighthearted efforts that offer little insight ("Obsession") to discussions that provide a lot of technical information ("Scorched," which talks about how they set up and film the fiery effects) to one that tackles the sensitive issue of how the creators mixed the issue of gang murders with David Sinclair (Alimi Ballard) in "The O.G." That episode was problematic because the creators didn't want to link Sinclair, the show's key black agent, to gangs. He discusses his initial reaction to the episode and how his attitude changed after seeing the script and talking with the director. The other extras bloopers and two behind-the-scenes featurettes with Nicolas Falacci and Krumholtz aren't really worth viewing. (Enhanced widescreen, 2005-06, not rated but adult content for violence) L.A. Luebbert In "Combat Diary: The Marines of Lima Company" (audio: ***, video: ***, extras: ***) we get to see what it was like for one of the hardest-hit combat units in the war. Along with all their other gear, the Reserve unit from Columbus, Ohio, was equipped with home video cameras. This war documentary produced by A&E IndieFilms is raw. It is a firsthand account of what the real deal is in Iraq. The heat, the connection between the troops. The casualties. It is revealing to see the initial enthusiasm of the company and how that feeling changes as the reality of war sets in. For those who want to romanticize the war, it's not going to happen here. Wherever your political beliefs about the war in Iraq lie, watching this riveting DVD will show you another view from the vantage point of the warriors. Extras include bonus footage that was left out of the original offering. There is a very touching video greeting from a Marine who taped a birthday message to his daughter back home just a month before he was killed. There is also a slide show with commentary by three of the men who took the pictures and a biography/filmography of the director. (Enhanced widescreen, 2006, not rated but contains some very graphic material) Cliff Redding As "That 70s Show: Season Five" (audio: ***1/2, video: ***1/2, extras: **) gets rolling, Eric (Topher Grace), Donna (Laura Prepon), Kelso (Ashton Kutcher) and the gang are gearing up for their senior year of high school. For the series, much like many a star high-school athlete, it would be all downhill after that. But season five presents the cast and writing still in prime form and, arguably, at its peak of popularity. Guest appearances by Jessica Simpson and Luke Wilson, among others, help add spice to the goings-on. The set's weak lineup of extras continues an ongoing trend with this series. While the first couple of seasons feature some audio commentaries and other standard goodies, this set (and the previous two) includes a pair of rather weak featurettes sit-downs with Danny Masterson and Wilmer Valderrama as well as the original promos for each episode and "Season 5 in 5 Minutes," which offers a quick rundown of the season's main story arcs. These sets could be much more impressive if only Fox would put a little bit of pride into their work. (Fullscreen, 2002, not rated) Robert Hatfield In "Andy Milonakis: The Complete Second Season," (audio: ***, video: ***, extras: ****) the rapping Jewish kid from the Lower East Side only gets better. Part hidden-camera reality show, part sketch comedy and part, well, crazy, the MTV2 show thrives with a unique brand of comedy that's low-budget and childish think biting into a worm and finding an apple, or a tin-can phone that leaks creamed corn. This season Andy, who, because of a birth defect looks like a teenager but is in fact 30 years old, continues to terrorize old folks in the L.E.S and lampoon his dim-witted sidekick Ralphie. Fifteen extra skits are included each of them more silly and strange than the next as well as two music videos in which Andy does his cartoonish but surprisingly decent raps. Warning: This is only for the truly goofy it's like Tom Green drunk on soda. (Fullscreen, 2006, not rated) - Malcolm Venable When a TV show's title is too rude for print, it goes without saying that its content may be more than a little risque. The magician duo at the helm of "Penn & Teller: Bulls**t! The Complete Third Season" (audio: ***, video, ***, extras, no stars) certainly haven't run out of opinions to express or dubious claims to debunk. They are hostile to conspiracy theories, government intrusion, organized religion, self-help mumbo-jumbo, the paranormal and silly toupees which is to say, viewers never know whether they'll be entertained, offended, or both. In the raucous, profanity-laced third season, the Showtime show takes on hair obsessions, circumcision (you can imagine the visual aids employed), gun control, family values, life coaching, religious relics (such as the Virgin Mary grilled-cheese sandwich), the Endangered Species Act and America's relentless quest for the best. The show is sometimes cruel and bombastic, but so gleefully irreverent that it's hard to stay angry for long. How upset can you get with a show that dares to show exactly yes, exactly what a bikini wax entails? Although there's plenty to enjoy in the third season, there's nothing extra to cheer about on this three-disc set. The only goodies are a lame collection of publicity photos and a list of the duo's movie and TV credits no outtakes, extra footage or commentaries. Packaging three discs with no decent extras? As Penn Jillette would say, that's a load of well, you get the drift. (Fullscreen, 2005, not rated) Caroline Luzzatto Three minor Michael Caine films are out as part of 20th Century Fox's Cinema Classics Collection. The biggest disappointment is "The Magus" (audio: ***, video: ***, extras: **), based on John Fowles' bestselling novel. Fowles wrote the screenplay of this convoluted, pretentious movie, starring Caine as Nicholas, an English teacher assigned to a school on a little Greek island. When Nicholas meets an enigmatic character named Maurice (Anthony Quinn) who lives with a beautiful young woman (Candice Bergen), the weirdness begins. Meanwhile, Nicholas is involved in a troubled relationship with a stewardess (Anna Karina), who appears from time to time in flashbacks. What is actually going on in the story is anyone's guess. There are plays within plays, masquerades, hints of magic and insanity, replete with awkward, purple prose. The one extra on this disc is a somewhat interesting documentary on Fowles, containing interviews with his biographer, fans, a literature professor and his editor at Little, Brown. In discussing "The Magus," Fowles' first novel, which took him 10 years to write, the prof sees the themes as true love and the meaning of life. His editor calls him the "best prose stylist of the 20th century." (Enhanced wide screen, 1968, rated PG) In "Deadfall" (audio: ***, video: ***, extras: **1/2), Caine is a jewel thief who is sucked into an elaborate heist scheme with an unlikely married couple. There is enough going on in this (comparatively) well-written film to keep it interesting. One special feature offers the isolated score, composed by John Barry. There is also a documentary on Barry and his illustrious career. The English composer was responsible for the James Bond soundtracks, "Out of Africa," "Body Heat," "The Lion in Winter," and hundreds more. Barry has a bit part in "Deadfall" as the conductor of a beautiful guitar symphony he composed. (Enhanced wide screen, 1968, rated R for nudity and sexual situations) "Peeper" (audio: **, video: ***, extras: **) stars Caine as Leslie Tucker, an L.A. private eye in 1947, hired by an eccentric wealthy man to find his adult daughter, who had been adopted as a child, so he can give her her rightful inheritance. Tucker finds the right family but isn't sure which of the daughters (played by Natalie Wood and Kitty Winn) is the lucky one. This spoof of a film noir is mildly entertaining, but definitely a grade B-minus. Extras include an interview with the director, Peter Hyams, who confesses to being a "Raymond Chandler freak." Hyams refers to the box office failure of the film as one of the "scars" in his life. In another, much more enjoyable, extra, film noir is examined in general. Clips from classic '40s movies are shown, as are more modern ones from the "rebirth" of the genre, with examples like "Chinatown" and "Taxi Driver." (Enhanced widescreen, 1975, rated PG) Peggy Earle

text: VirginianPilot-tDVD jacket for "Over the Hedge" from DreamWorks Animation and Paramount Home Entertainment. "Over the Hedge" It's about a band of critters who wake up from hibernation in the spring to discover a hedge separating them from the 'burbs. At first, they're scared of the tall, foreboding bush, which they call "Steve" for lack of a better name, until R.J. the raccoon (Bruce Willis) shows them the utopia in suburbia. The movie, based on the popular cartoon of the same name, is smartly written and has wonderful computer animation a glimpse of which you get in the extra features. Not only is the story fun, but the DVD is packed with great extras including a couple not-so-easy games, such as the Skee-Ball-like Hammy Nut Toss. Commentary by directors Tim Johnson, Karey Kirkpatrick and producer Bonnie Arnold shows their pride in the whole package, from which effects were the hardest to animate to some of Thomas Haden Church's ad-libs as exterminator Dwayne. Other extras worth watching include a new animated short, "Hammy's Boomerang Adventure," "Dwayne's Verm-Tech Infomercial" and a look at the actors who do the voices, including Portsmouth's own Wanda Sykes as Stella the skunk. (Enhanced widescreen, 2006, rated PG for some rude humor and mild comic action) Toni Guagenti Inline image:VirginianPilot-tHD-DVD/DVD comb disc jacket for "The Break-Up" from Universal Studios Home Entertainment. In brief, "The Break-Up" (audio, ***, video: ***1/2, extras: ****) is "Swingers" revisited. So if you're looking for light, romantic comedy, this isn't it. But if you want a blend of comedy and drama and don't mind revisiting some dialogues . you may have had in the past, then spend time with Vince Vaughn, Jennifer Aniston and the splendid cast including Jon Favreau, Jason Bateman, Joey Lauren Adams and Vincent D'Onofrio that plays their family and friends. Viewers will find conflict as soon as the DVD and HD-DVD opens. You'll get to pick a "his side" or "her side" to watch the film. It's the same movie no matter what you pick, but can't you picture couples fighting for the remote? Vaughn co-wrote and produced the film and provides an in-depth commentary. Aniston is also featured, although she's strictly support. A second commentary with director Peyton Reed is also worthwhile. But what truly makes the DVD worth its price is an alternate ending, similar to the theater version, except that it also features the hilarious Tone Rangers and their leader, John Michael Higgins. The HD version of "Break-Up" brings a bigger pop in picture and sound. It also has the "U Control" feature that allows viewers to watch highlights from the extras as the film runs. Make sure you're up-to-date with the latest firmware software (2.0 version) for your Toshiba HD-DVD player, to use the U Control feature. (HD widescreen & enhanced widescreen, 2006, rated PG-13 for sexual content, some nudity and language) Kay Reynolds Inline image:VirginianPilot-tDVD jacket for "Feast:Unrated" from The Weinstein Company. "Feast" (audio:***, video:***, extras:**1/2) is the third film born from the reality television series "Project Greenlight," spearheaded by Ben Affleck, Matt Damon and Chris Moore. While the show is terrific, the resulting films have been lackluster straight-to-video fare. With the threat of cancellation looming, the third season was devoted to making a commercially viable horror film, and the filmmakers may have succeeded. (Enhanced widescreen, 2006, unrated) Josh Boone Inline image:VirginianPilot-t Is it blasphemy to remake a classic film? Maybe if we were talking about "Casablanca." Making a hands-off case for "The Omen" (audio, ***, video, ***1/2, extras, ****) isn't as easy. The original, directed by Richard Donner and starring Gregory Peck and Lee Remick as the duped parents, was released in 1976. Honestly, it was difficult to believe that Peck so well known for his role as Atticus Finch in "To Kill a Mockingbird" could be thwarted by the devil's child. Would Peck/Finch lie to his wife about replacing their baby? Take us up to 2006 with a new cast and the plot is easier to swallow. So are the new, state of the art visual effects. Director John Moore, who also filmed the remake of "Flight of the Phoenix," was visited by the "Omen" curse while rushing the film for release on June 6, 2006 all the better to take advantage of "Number of the Beast" tie in. Viewers can get the details in Moore's commentary and in a featurette, "Omenisms." Additional supernatural lore is explored in "Revelation 666," but it's a choppy piece no pun intended. You'll find better on The Discovery and Sci-Fi channels. An additional feature on the score, deleted and extended scenes, with commentary, round out the standard extras for decent Halloween party viewing. The film is a near scene-for-scene remake. It's the cast, including Liev Schreiber, Julia Stiles, Pete Postlethwaite, David Thewlis and a particularly scary little boy, Seamus Davey-Fitzpatrick, who'll hold your interest. Mia Farrow shows up, too, as an especially protective nanny who would be perfect in a "Halloween"-type remake of "Mary Poppins." (Enhanced widescreen, 2006, rated for disturbing violent content, graphic images and some language) Kay Reynolds Inline image:VirginianPilot-t During the turbulent 1960s, an unwritten rule dominated college basketball in Texas. You never play more than one black basketball player at home. Two if you're on the road and three only if you're losing. Coach Don Haskins (Josh Lucas) at tiny Texas Western University in El Paso wanted to win and that meant bucking the system. After searching far and wide, Haskins selected seven African-American players, mostly from north of the Mason-Dixon Line. By season's end, Texas Western made it to a national championship and defeated an all-white Kentucky team under legendary coach Adolph Rupp. NBA coach and Kentucky guard Pat Riley calls the victory the "emancipation proclamation of 1966" during an interview at the closing credits. The inspirational "Glory Road" (audio: ****, video: ****, extras: **) shines in high-def Blu-ray, with a spectacular picture and uncompressed digital sound, but Disney shortchanged the extras. Two documentaries featured on the low-tech DVD have vanished, one that highlighted Haskins' 30-year-plus career, the other that included interviews with his players and colleagues. Two commentaries are intact, including one with first-time director James Gartner, handpicked by producer Jerry Bruckheimer. Gartner is quite open about his shortcomings, wishing he had tightened a few scenes, but details the racial tension on-screen in scenes with Bobby Joe Hill (Derek Luke). "Luke's character is full of quiet anger, as benched talent," Gartner says, since most black players of his era never saw action in the South. (Enhanced wide-screen, 2006, unrated) - Josh Boone Eloise is an imp with a heart and her personality shines through on IDT Entertainment's new line of animated stories, including the new releases "Me, Eloise" and "Eloise: Little Miss Christmas" (both: audio: ***, video: ***, extras: ***). Staying true to the character's precociousness, the creators have made up great storylines that show Eloise's curious, creative personality and her ability to be inclusive and generous. In the first show, Eloise makes friends with an 8-year-old violin prodigy from Tokyo who moves into New York's famous Plaza Hotel. Eloise teaches Yuko and her parents that there is more to life than practicing the violin. In the Christmas show, Eloise and her Plaza pals go to great lengths in the face of many roadblocks to put on a yuletide show for some of New York's downtrodden. New characters are introduced, but they stay true to the fun and antics. Lynn Redgrave voices Nanny, Eloise's guardian when her mother's not around, and Tim Curry voices Plaza manager Mr. Salamone; both do fabulous jobs in those roles. The extras are quite fun, too. Other extras include a quick look at some of the shows' characters as narrated by Eloise, a different game on each of the DVDs and a look at sketches and the final animated product that run simultaneously on the screen it's pretty neat. Eloise creator Kay Thompson is rumored to have based her books on her own life, as well as that of her goddaughter, Liza Minelli and she would probably get a kick out of this version of her famous creation. (Both: Enhanced widescreen and fullscreen, 2006, not rated) - Toni Guagenti The bonus, in and of itself, is owning "It's The Great Pumpkin, Charlie Brown" (audio: ****, video, ****, extras: *) on DVD. So don't get excited, because that story and a bonus feature, "You're Not Elected, Charlie Brown," are all you get on this "Peanuts Classic" release. "You blockhead!" she screams at him, realizing she's missed out on the candy-collecting. Plus, she can't get any goodies from her brother, because all he got was rocks. This classic can be enjoyed over and over again. In the second feature, Charlie Brown doesn't get to run for class office because Lucy's unscientific polling discovers no one would vote for him. Poor Charlie Brown. But Linus gets a shot and almost blows it after promising the kids a visit from the Great Pumpkin as part of his platform. The colors pop on this DVD, including the vivid hues of Linus' red tee, Lucy's blue dress and Charlie Brown's yellow shirt. The music's in Dolby Digital, and Vince Guaraldi's score is perfect. (Fullscreen, 1966, not rated) Toni Guagenti Peter Bogdanovich's "They All Laughed: 25th Anniversary Edition" (audio: ***, video: ***, extras:***) features Audrey Hepburn in her final starring role in a theatrical film. Although both Quentin Tarantino and Wes Anderson consider it one of their favorite films of all time, it was a huge bomb when it was originally released and nearly destroyed Bogdanovich. Actress Dorothy Stratten was murdered after the film's shooting was completed and studios distanced themselves from the film, refusing to release it because of the bad publicity surrounding the tragedy. Bogdanovich put in $5 million of his own money and distributed the film himself. The shooting was also plagued by tension on the set between Hepburn and actor Ben Gazzara, who had recently split up with Hepburn to marry another woman. Twenty-five years have put enough distance between the behind-the-scenes drama to make it possible to appreciate this tremendously fun, if slight, screwball comedy about a team of detectives who get involved with two women they are investigating for suspected adultery. The DVD includes a video conversation between Bogdanovich and Anderson and a thoroughly enjoyable commentary by Bogdanovich. (Enhanced wide-screen, 1981, rated PG) - Josh Boone "Numb3rs: The Complete Second Season" (audio: ***, video: ***, extras: ***1/2) builds on the half-season that got the series off to a solid start. Forget struggles to de-randomize shooting sprees; mathematician Charlie Eppes (David Krumholtz) helps his brother Don (Rob Morrow) and other FBI agents solve arsons, stalkings and robberies this season. The set offers seven episodes with commentaries that run the gamut from lighthearted efforts that offer little insight ("Obsession") to discussions that provide a lot of technical information ("Scorched," which talks about how they set up and film the fiery effects) to one that tackles the sensitive issue of how the creators mixed the issue of gang murders with David Sinclair (Alimi Ballard) in "The O.G." That episode was problematic because the creators didn't want to link Sinclair, the show's key black agent, to gangs. He discusses his initial reaction to the episode and how his attitude changed after seeing the script and talking with the director. The other extras bloopers and two behind-the-scenes featurettes with Nicolas Falacci and Krumholtz aren't really worth viewing. (Enhanced widescreen, 2005-06, not rated but adult content for violence) L.A. Luebbert In "Combat Diary: The Marines of Lima Company" (audio: ***, video: ***, extras: ***) we get to see what it was like for one of the hardest-hit combat units in the war. Along with all their other gear, the Reserve unit from Columbus, Ohio, was equipped with home video cameras. This war documentary produced by A&E IndieFilms is raw. It is a firsthand account of what the real deal is in Iraq. The heat, the connection between the troops. The casualties. It is revealing to see the initial enthusiasm of the company and how that feeling changes as the reality of war sets in. For those who want to romanticize the war, it's not going to happen here. Wherever your political beliefs about the war in Iraq lie, watching this riveting DVD will show you another view from the vantage point of the warriors. Extras include bonus footage that was left out of the original offering. (Fullscreen, 2002, not rated) Robert Hatfield In "Andy Milonakis: The Complete Second Season," (audio: ***, video: ***, extras: ****) the rapping Jewish kid from the Lower East Side only gets better. Part hidden-camera reality show, part sketch comedy and part, well, crazy, the MTV2 show thrives with a unique brand of comedy that's low-budget and childish think biting into a worm and finding an apple, or a tin-can phone that leaks creamed corn. This season Andy, who, because of a birth defect looks like a teenager but is in fact 30 years old, continues to terrorize old folks in the L.E.S and lampoon his dim-witted sidekick Ralphie. (Fullscreen, 2006, not rated) - Malcolm Venable When a TV show's title is too rude for print, it goes without saying that its content may be more than a little risque. The magician duo at the helm of "Penn & Teller: Bulls**t! The Complete Third Season" (audio: ***, video, ***, extras, no stars) certainly haven't run out of opinions to express or dubious claims to debunk. They are hostile to conspiracy theories, government intrusion, organized religion, self-help mumbo-jumbo, the paranormal and silly toupees which is to say, viewers never know whether they'll be entertained, offended, or both. In the raucous, profanity-laced third season, the Showtime show takes on hair obsessions, circumcision (you can imagine the visual aids employed), gun control, family values, life coaching, religious relics (such as the Virgin Mary grilled-cheese sandwich), the Endangered Species Act and America's relentless quest for the best. The show is sometimes cruel and bombastic, but so gleefully irreverent that it's hard to stay angry for long. How upset can you get with a show that dares to show exactly yes, exactly what a bikini wax entails? Although there's plenty to enjoy in the third season, there's nothing extra to cheer about on this three-disc set. The only goodies are a lame collection of publicity photos and a list of the duo's movie and TV credits no outtakes, extra footage or commentaries. Packaging three discs with no decent extras? As Penn Jillette would say, that's a load of well, you get the drift. (Fullscreen, 2005, not rated) Caroline Luzzatto Three minor Michael Caine films are out as part of 20th Century Fox's Cinema Classics Collection. The biggest disappointment is "The Magus" (audio: ***, video: ***, extras: **), based on John Fowles' bestselling novel. Fowles wrote the screenplay of this convoluted, pretentious movie, starring Caine as Nicholas, an English teacher assigned to a school on a little Greek island. When Nicholas meets an enigmatic character named Maurice (Anthony Quinn) who lives with a beautiful young woman (Candice Bergen), the weirdness begins. Meanwhile, Nicholas is involved in a troubled relationship with a stewardess (Anna Karina), who appears from time to time in flashbacks. What is actually going on in the story is anyone's guess. There are plays within plays, masquerades, hints of magic and insanity, replete with awkward, purple prose. The one extra on this disc is a somewhat interesting documentary on Fowles, containing interviews with his biographer, fans, a literature professor and his editor at Little, Brown. In discussing "The Magus," Fowles' first novel, which took him 10 years to write, the prof sees the themes as true love and the meaning of life. His editor calls him the "best prose stylist of the 20th century." (Enhanced wide screen, 1968, rated PG) In "Deadfall" (audio: ***, video: ***, extras: **1/2), Caine is a jewel thief who is sucked into an elaborate heist scheme with an unlikely married couple. There is enough going on in this (comparatively) well-written film to keep it interesting. One special feature offers the isolated score, composed by John Barry. There is also a documentary on Barry and his illustrious career. The English composer was responsible for the James Bond soundtracks, "Out of Africa," "Body Heat," "The Lion in Winter," and hundreds more. Barry has a bit part in "Deadfall" as the conductor of a beautiful guitar symphony he composed. (Enhanced wide screen, 1968, rated R for nudity and sexual situations) "Peeper" (audio: **, video: ***, extras: **) stars Caine as Leslie Tucker, an L.A. private eye in 1947, hired by an eccentric wealthy man to find his adult daughter, who had been adopted as a child, so he can give her her rightful inheritance. Tucker finds the right family but isn't sure which of the daughters (played by Natalie Wood and Kitty Winn) is the lucky one. This spoof of a film noir is mildly entertaining, but definitely a grade B-minus. Extras include an interview with the director, Peter Hyams, who confesses to being a "Raymond Chandler freak." Clips from classic '40s movies are shown, as are more modern ones from the "rebirth" of the genre, with examples like "Chinatown" and "Taxi Driver." (Enhanced widescreen, 1975, rated PG) Peggy Earle

"A PRAIRIE HOME Companion" Peggy Earle Inline image:VirginianPilot-quotDVD box set for the "Motion Pictures Masterpiece Collection" from Warner Bros. Home Video. THERE WAS A TIME when studios relied on novels loved by a well-read audience as a source for movie magic. We now can find a brilliant sampling of these inspired gems in Warner Brothers' five-disc set: "Motion Picture Masterpieces Collection: 'David Copperfield' (1935), 'Marie Antoinette' (1938), 'Pride and Prejudice' (1940), 'A Tale of Two Cities' (1935) and 'Treasure Island' (1934)" (audio, ***, video, ***, extras, *** ). Each disc includes vintage cartoons and featurettes for a full night at the movies. Many of these, such as "Strikes and Spares," were Oscar-nominated. Today they are far from PC and unintentionally funny. The real prizes are the films. No one has ever played Sydney Carton better than Ronald Colman in "A Tale of Two Cities." Colman's Carton is a charmer: Men like him, women love him and his sacrifice still brings tears. Elizabeth Allan, in the role of Lucie Manette, is incandescent. She plays such a kindly character, a beacon of decency. It would have been so easy to go over the top, but she doesn't. Basil Rathbone is in fine form as the evil Marquis St. Evremonde. He also shows up as the equally villainous Edward Murdstone in "David Copperfield," along with W.C. Fields and Freddy Bartholomew. There is a great game in watching these classics back to back and spotting reappearing actors: Maureen O'Sullivan, Edna May Oliver, the Barrymores and others. (All: Black and white, full-screen, not rated) Kay Reynolds Inline image:VirginianPilot-quotHD-DVD jacket for "Charlie and the Chocolate Factory" from Warner Bros. Home Video. Tim Burton's "Corpse Bride" and "Charlie and the Chocolate Factory" (both: audio: ****, video: ****, extras: ****) look spectacular in their new HD presentation. Images are sharp and colors are distinct on new screens and old. And viewers, young and old, should find this a delight. Burton has developed a repertoire of actors, including Johnny Depp, Christopher Lee and Helena Bonham Carter, all featured players in both films. Danny Elfman brings his distinctive touch to each very musical score. "Charlie and the Chocolate Factory" offers the "In-Movie Experience" among its extras. Hosted by an Oompa-Loompa, you can watch special background material as the film runs. Unfortunately, the "Experience" provides nothing you can't find among the various documentaries. It also takes you all the way back to the beginning of the film if switched on while the movie is in progress. "Corpse Bride" offers the same extras available on the original DVD release and are still great fun to watch. Elfman offers his interpretation of the music he composed for the human world and the Underworld. A music-only track enhances his description and might make great Halloween party background. "Corpse Bride" is also available in Blu-ray. Fans of the original Candy Man, Gene Wilder, will be pleased to see David L. Wolper's "Willy Wonka & the Chocolate Factory" (audio: ****, video: ****, extras: ***) is also available on glorious HD. Commentary from the child actors is filled with anecdotes. (Burton films: HD widescreen, 2005. "Corpse Bride" rated PG for some scary images and action, and brief, mild language. Kay Reynolds Inline image:VirginianPilot-quot Adam Sandler may be Hollywood's surest bet. Five of his last six movies have nearly doubled their profits. His latest is "Click," (audio: ****, video: ****, extras: ** ) which is available in DVD and Blu-ray as the first 50-gigabyte disc. It worked flawlessly on my Samsung BD player. Sandler plays Michael Newman, a workaholic architect with two kids and a beautiful wife (Kate Beckinsale), who finds himself enslaved to his dozen remotes which control every gadget under the roof. Trying to simplify his life, Michael needs a universal remote. First stop, Best Buy. It's closed. He then wanders into Bed Bath and Beyond and meets Morty (Christopher Walken) behind a mysterious door in the workshop and is given the ultimate remote. This truly magical gadget starts controlling Michael's life. He can pause a scene, mute the barking dog, skip life's bad stuff and reverse to his birth. What he discovers is he's missing out on life. Trying to bridge the gap between another juvenile Sandler comedy and Frank Capra's "It's a Wonderful Life," "Click" quickly becomes sappy and predictable, so keep your remote handy to fast-forward to the end. The disc includes a commentary with director Frank Coraci, college bud of Sandler at NYU, executive producer Tim Herlihy, screenwriter Steve Koren and Sandler. During the commentary, they brag about shooting on high-def video, not film, making it their format of choice. Also, the half-dozen short documentaries are in HD, highlighting the makeup process Sandler becoming old and fat special effects and more. (HD widescreen, 2006, PG-13 for language, crude and sex-related humor and some drug references) Bill Kelley III Inline image:VirginianPilot-quot Finally, an A-list movie worthy of everyone's HD-DVD collection. "Batman Begins" (audio: ****, video: ****, extras: ** ) gets the epic treatment, similar to Richard Donner's "Superman: The Movie" with Christopher Reeves playing the Man of Steel which is planned for HD-DVD and Blu-ray this November. Brit director Christopher Nolan ("Memento" and "Insomnia") gives this comic book classic an emotional core that previous "Batman" movies clearly missed telling Bruce Wayne's origins, a young boy tormented by his fears. Too bad the HD disc has such an uninspired pop-up video commentary. The short clips just highlight the eight documentaries. You can watch them in their entirety in the bonus section. That's where you'll get Nolan's complete journey spending weeks in a back room off his garage, working with co-writer David S. Goyer, translating the tale. They were so secretive; they gave "Batman Begins" an alias "Intimidation Game" and studio execs had to spend the afternoon between the washer and dryer reading the script for the first time. The other documentaries are quite informative including Christian Bale's training and rehearsing becoming the superhero; costume design for the Batsuit; creation of the Batmobile; filming in Iceland the world beyond Gotham City; CGI and production design of Gotham, Batcave and Wayne Manor. The disc also includes the uncompressed Dolby TrueHD track for exceptional dynamic range, the clearest digital sound possible surpassing your DVD and anything at the multiplex. (HD widescreen, 2005, PG-13 for intense action violence, disturbing images and some thematic elements) Bill Kelley III Two previous Warner Bros. HD-DVDs premiere on Blu-ray (BD) this week. Warner is one of three studios supporting both HD formats which aren't compatible with each other. It's 8:02 a.m., New York City Detective Jack Mosley (Bruce Willis), a repetitious drunk, has one more job before heading home: transport petty criminal Eddie Bunker (Mos Def), "16 Blocks" (audio: ****, video: ****, extras: *1/2) from the precinct stationhouse to the courthouse, by 10 a.m. Oblivious to the hung-over detective, hired assassins are on his tail, to stop motormouth Bunker from testifying against one of NYC's worst cops and his co-horts which includes Mosley. For the next 100 minutes, you're in for a wild ride through Manhattan especially after Mosley's pit stop at his favorite liquor store exposing Bunker to the killers. The BD discs sports an identical crystal-clear picture as the HD-DVD, but just like its high def cousin, it can't seamlessly insert the shocking alternate ending which worked perfectly on the DVD. "It's the ending we intended, once we started filming," says director Richard Donner ("Superman" "Lethal Weapon"). The theatrical edit, is really the "alternate" ending, says Donner and writer Richard Wenk. The duo provided a commentary for 20 minutes of deleted scenes as they explain how each ended up on the cutting room floor. Rapper/actor Mos Def's performance is quite good, making this buddy flick worth a spin on your BD or HD-DVD player. (HD widescreen, 2006, PG-13 for violence, intense sequences of action, and some strong language) Bill Kelley III Oil is the drug of the 21st Century and governments the new cartels in "Syriana" (audio: ***, video: ****, extras: ***). And the battle is only just beginning. Whether viewing in BD or HD-DVD, don't skip the interviews. Director/writer Stephen Gaghan of "Traffic" and former CIA operative Robert "Bob" Baer penned this nonpartisan testimony to the strategies of big oil. Baer is a fascinating been-there-done-that speaker who puts a face on complicated issues. It would be great to hear more from him. "Syriana" is as complicated as its subject and best viewed without distraction. Follow a rogue agent who runs with the wolves of change in Beirut. An economist's family tragedy creates a bond with an idealistic prince. Two major oil companies explore merger. A desperate young man is wooed by a charismatic cultist. Shadow operatives plot who will inherit after an old man's death. Blink and you lose a thread. Like "Traffic," individual storylines weave together to a powerful climax. George Clooney earned a Best Supporting Oscar for his mirror-role as CIA agent Bob Barnes. He is supported by an outstanding cast including Matt Damon, Christopher Plummer, Jeffrey Wright, Kayvan Novak, Amr Waked, Chris Cooper, and Alexander Siddig. (HD widescreen, 2005, R for violence and language.) Kay Reynolds Inline image:VirginianPilot-quot What would you do if your child was in the back seat of your car when it got hijacked? Well, that is the premise of "Waist Deep" (audio: ***1/2, video: ***1/2, extras: **). This gritty, urban film (directed by Vonde Curtis Hall) is about an ex-con (Tyrese), who is trying to do the right thing by raising his son and keeping in the good graces at his security job. He's trying to be a regular Joe, albeit in the hood, when his son winds up in the hands of some Los Angeles gang members. Tyrese, O2, is forced to get down and dirty in order to get his son back. O2 has to come up with $100,000 to get Junior back. And by doing so, O2 has to resort to his criminal side. The action is somewhat predictable, although entertaining. The film also stars Larenz Tate and Meagan Good. Extras include a making-of featurette titled "Drive-by Filmmaking," deleted scenes and a "slamming" music video by Black Buddafly featuring Fabolous.
