Thou, it doesn't include Stan Lee's custom comic book the extras included aren't too shabby. The DVD comes with two commentaries from director Brett Ratner and screenwriters Simon Kinberg and Zak Penn and the second from the producers. The commentaries do have a nice sarcastic tone, at one point making mention of the difficulty Ben Foster had growing wings for his role as Angel. The deleted scenes are a nice addition. They range from alternate takes (one including a bearded Magneto), to extended scenes (for instance, the cool fight scene at Jean Grey's house) and three alternate endings. The deleted scenes are by far the best of the extras. This is not a bad buy for any fan of the movie. (Enhanced widescreen, 2006, PG-13 for intense sequences of action violence, some sexual content and language) Brian Shapiro Sitcoms lasting more than a season or two tend to follow a similar trajectory. They start off a little off-kilter, pick up a great deal of steam that can last for two to three seasons and then begin cooling off. There are few exceptions. "Scrubs: Season Four" (audio ***1/2, video ****, extras ***) is one of those exceptions. The top-shelf ensemble cast remains as top-to-bottom funny as ever. Season four's string of guest stars (Heather Graham, Colin Farrell, Matthew Perry and Molly Shannon, to name a few) remains impressive and adds just enough spice to an already-tasty mix. The writing by this point has become a tad redundant, but certainly not enough to hamper the laugh fest. If anything sullies this release, it's the recent Scrubs syndication deal that puts episodes on a number of channels (most notably Comedy Central) every evening of the week. Still, season four highlights like "My Boss' Free Haircut", which showcases the brilliant Ken Jenkins as Dr. Kelso, and "My Life in Four Cameras" which briefly re-imagines the series as filmed like a traditional sitcom redeem this set. A reasonably worthwhile batch of extras is highlighted by "Will You Be My Mentor," which chronicles JD's (Zach Braff) seemingly endless quest for Dr. Cox's (John C. McGinley) approval. Also worth checking out are a witty look at Neil Flynn's janitor character, entitled "Who Is This Man?" and "The Weapons Chest," which celebrates the series' "second string" cast members, most notably Sam Lloyd, who plays the flop-sweat drenched hospital lawyer, Ted. A pair of commentaries help round out an otherwise forgettable remaining string of features. (Fullscreen, 2005, not rated) Robert Hatfield Though well-directed and acted, "The King" (audio: ***1/2, video: ***1/2, extras: **1/2) is a gut-wrenching film with few redeeming qualities that I would have a hard time recommending to anyone. Gael Garcia Bernal ("Y Tu Mama Tambien," "The Science of Sleep"), one of the most gifted actors working today, gives a chilling performance as Elvis, the illegitimate son of a Texas preacher (played by William Hurt). After a stint in the Navy he shows up in Corpus Christi and attempts to be a part of his father's life, who wants nothing to do with him since he fathered him before he became a Christian. This pushes Elvis over the edge and he murders Hurt's teenage son and seduces and impregnates his sixteen-year-old daughter, who also happens to be his half sister. This is just the beginning of the nastiness you'll see in "The King." It's a bad sign when the DVD includes a letter from the filmmakers who feel they need to defend their film instead of allowing it to speak for itself. The biggest problem with "The King" is that we never get inside Elvis's head to understand his actions. He takes on a detached and malevolent aura and almost seems to represent Satan, who has come to destroy this God fearing family. The DVD includes a commentary with writer/producer Milo Addica and writer/director James Marsh and deleted scenes. Though the film has failures on a writing level, I applaud the filmmakers for portraying a Christian family without making them look like clowns. (Enhanced widescreen, 2005, R for strong sexuality involving a teen, violence and language) Josh Boone "Bad Santa" (audio: ***, video: ***, extras: ***) is not your usual Christmas story. Billy Bob Thornton is an alcolholic, womanizer who poses as Santa, and, with the help of his "Little Helper" (played by Tony Cox), makes a living by ripping off department stores on Christmas Eve. Their scam is working, until Thornton's Willie gets his heart tugged by a troubled little boy who gets under his skin. To add to the chaos, the store's security boss (Bernie Mac) is onto the duo's scam. Thornton's Willie is ridiculous as the Santa from hell, hitting on women in plain view of the kids, showing up to work drunk. Image the most obnoxious person you can think of. Now imagine them in a Santa Claus suit . and multiply that by 50. John Ritter even turns in a funny performance (one of his last) as Bob Chipeska, store manager. Extras include a making-of featurette, deleted and alternate scenes, and commentary with the film's editor, Robert Hoffman, and director Terry Zwigoff. (Enhanced widescreen, 2003, rated R for language and adult situations) Cliff Redding Ridley Scott faced many challenges while filming "Black Rain: Special Collector's Edition" (audio: ***1/2, video: ***1/2, extras: ***1/2) in Japan. He had so much trouble getting the locations he wanted and the time he needed to shoot there that a surprising amount of footage ended up being shot back in the states. Michael Douglas and Andy Garcia play New York cops who find themselves in the middle of a gang war between the Yakuza and the Japanese Mafia. Scott's signature look (perfected in "Blade Runner" and "Alien") are on display and this marks Scott's first collaboration with composer Hans Zimmer. The DVD features a stunning new transfer, showing none of the print damage evident in the earlier bare bones release. Extras include a commentary by Scott and roughly an hour of documentaries covering the film's frustrating production, the editing process (the film was whittled down from nearly three hours) and the reaction of critics after the film's release. Paramount has done a terrific job. Ridley Scott fans take note. (Enhanced widescreen, 1989, R for violence and language) Josh Boone Out of sensitivity to the feelings of Americans less than five years after Sept. 11, the "CSI:NY" creators waited until the end of season two to deal with a bomb blast in a building and also had a back story that made "Charge of This Post" about more than just a possible terrorist attack. That is one of the things viewers will learn on the extras with "CSI - NY: The Complete Second Season" (audio: ***1/2, video: ***, extras: ***1/2). The back story, including flashbacks by Mac Taylor (Gary Sinise) to his time as a Marine during the Beirut bombing, was one part of a series of changes for season two. It allowed for a broadening of character development. Another big change is season two was the general atmosphere, going from dark to lighter. Most of the commentaries at least touch on this, and there are features that examine some of the changes, including ones to the set and cast. (Enhanced widescreen, 2005-06, not rated but some violence and adult issues such as rape) L.A. Luebbert Maybe Disney was too busy putting together "The Little Mermaid: Platinum Edition" to worry about upgrading or beefing up its 25th anniversary edition of "The Fox and the Hound" (audio: **1/2, video: **1/2, extras: ***). Regardless, this little ditty about a fox named "Tod" and a hound named "Copper" is a sweet tale about friendship, even though the two when they meet as youngsters don't know they're mortal enemies. Bonus features aren't new and are typical Disney with a "Forest Friendship Game," where you find Tod or match other forest creatures with their best friends; a story read-along or read-alone extra; "The Fox and the Hound" art gallery; two Disney old shorts, "Lambert The Sheepish Lion" and "Lend a Paw," nice stories about acceptance and friendship; and "The Best of Friends" sing-along song crooned by the late, great Pearl Bailey, the voice of Big Mama (owl) in the movie. Although it's short, "Passing the Baton: The Making Of The Fox and the Hound" featurette explains why this movie marked the studio's rise once again to the top of the animation world. It talks about Walt Disney's famous "Nine Old Men," animators that made "Snow White" and "Bambi" such masterpieces, as they handed over the reigns to new artists during the making of "The Fox and the Hound." A connection to "The Little Mermaid" in this featurette: two of the movie's animators went on to score big with Ariel and the gang eight years later Ron Clements and John Musker both co-directors and writers on the mermaid movie. (Fullscreen, 1981, rated G) Toni Guagenti Since NBC put the addictive Emmy-winning show's third season on hold, fans will have to be satisfied watching "Medium: The Complete Second Season" (audio: ***, video: ***1/2, extras: ***) until new episodes start running. (Soon, please!) Patricia Arquett, Jake Weber, Miguel Sandoval and David Cubitt return for 22 fascinating episodes here along with some top-notch guest stars, such as Molly Ringwald and David Carradine. Returning regulars include Connor O'Farrell as the shifty defense attorney, Ryan Hurst as the Medium's brother, psycho/psychic killer Mark A. Sheppard, and Arliss Howard as Capt. Kenneth Push, who brings a rip-snorting showdown to Season One's end season cliffhanger and second season opener, "When Push Comes to Shove." We also get to see executive producer Kelsey Grammer take a turn as the Angel of Death in "Death Takes a Policy." He is absolutely perfect as always. The beauty of "Medium's" mysteries is that they are mysterious. They are great puzzlers that challenge your smarts, without resorting to trickery. Viewers get the same clues as our heroine and her companions. (Viewers also get two pair of 3-D glasses enclosed in this 6-disc set, the better to watch the 3-D episode, "Sill Life 2-D," where paintings take on a life their own. A 2-D version of the episode is also included.) Happily, viewers can enjoy Season 2 without having seen the first season. The series follows the trials and victories of Allison DuBois, a woman who helps solve crimes using intuition, dreams and some spontaneous mind reading. "Medium" packs more punch, heart and believability than "Ghost Whisperer." Extras include scattered commentaries by creator/writer Glenn Gordon Caron ("Moonlighting") and others. Caron is also featured in the documentaries that cover Season 2 highlights and the 3-D episode. Fans of the young actresses who play the DuBois daughters, Sofia Vassilleva and Maria Lark, can enjoy a "A Day in the Life" featurette. (Enhanced widescreen, 2, not rated, but beware of adult themes and implied violence) Kay Reynolds A sentimental love story in an unusual setting "Changing Times" (audio: ***, video: ***, extras: **) was directed by Andre Techine and stars Catherine Deneuve and Gerard Depardieu, both stars (shall we say) slightly the worse for wear. In the story, the two had been passionate lovers in their youth. Thirty years later, Antoine (Depardieu) finds a way, via his work, to go to Tangiers, where he knows Cecile (Deneuve) lives. She is married to a younger man and has a grown son. Antoine, who had never married, nor forgotten Cecile, begins to send anonymous bouquets of roses to her at the radio station where she works. Eventually, he presents himself and she completely rejects him and sends him on his way. But her marriage is falling apart and the very predictable happens. Thanks to the high caliber of the acting and directing, this otherwise-sappy story is very watchable. The only special feature is an interview with the actor Gilbert Melki, who plays the younger husband. He discusses the way Techine directs with "no psychology" and "no improvising." Everything in the film, which was shot on location, had been written into the script, albeit sometimes immediately before the shooting. (Enhanced widescreen, 2004, unrated) The makers of "Ghost World" have conspired in another cynical, funny film: "Art School Confidential" (audio: ***1/2, video: ****, extras: ***). Written by Daniel Clowes and directed by Terry Zwigoff ("Crumb"), it stars Max Minghella (the director Anthony's son), Sophia Myles, John Malkovich, Anjelica Huston and Jim Broadbent. Though not as pitch-perfect as "Ghost World," this hits nerves often and funny bones even more. A young, sexually inexperienced man (Minghella) is a freshman at the fictional Strathmore (for art insiders, that's the brand of many art supplies) College in New York City. He gets quick doses of reality when it comes to girls, the art world, and his artistic heroes. A sub-plot concerns a serial killer stalking people on the college campus. Extras include a making-of documentary, in which Clowes says the story is autobiographical: "Art school was, to me, what Vietnam was to Oliver Stone!" A Sundance featurette includes brief interviews with all the actors at the Utah resort where the film had its world premiere this year. There are deleted scenes, a blooper reel and alternate takes of a scene with Malkovich. (Enhanced widescreen, 2005, R for language, nudity and violence) Peggy Earle Comedian Carlos Mencia will get you laughing . and living. And in "Carlos Mencia: No Strings Attached" (audio: ***, video: ***; extras: ***), the man brilliantly picks on each and every ethnic group: blacks, Asians, Middle Easterners, whites and of course Latinos. Mencia is merciless in his delivery during two offerings (actually three) of his stand-up routine. There is one that was taped for a Comedy Central "One Night Stand in New York" a little while after the Sept. 11 terrorist attacks, where he gets all over us in America for being, well, American. The humor is raw and not for the tenderhearted, but the man is funny. FUNNY, when you stop long enough to ponder what he is really say. In his more-recent "No Strings Attached" performance, Mencia even gets MORE raw with his brand of ethnic humor. He even picks on the pope. The pope AND Mother Teresa, as well as members of the groups previously named. The coolest thing about this DVD is that there are two versions of the "Attached" appearance, which was filmed in San Francisco. The first version is the one that the public saw on Comedy Central, the "tamer" of the two versions (and Comedy Central is not one known for being tame, you know). The second version gets more nasty. More "insensitive" (to some) and even more obnoxious. This is the extended, director's cut version, and Mencia manages to raise a few eyebrows here. He even seems to surprise himself by how far he goes with one of his routines. How about that, ladies and gentlemen? Extras on this DVD include the "Comedy Central Presents: Carlos Mencia" performance and a featurette on the making of the ridiculously cool chopper that Mencia rides onto the stage on in "No Strings." (Fullscreen, 2006, not rated but this DVD is for mature audiences only. Trust me on this.) Cliff Redding Television in the 1980s was as much about escapism as TV in the 21st century is about reality. From "Magnum P.I." to the "A-Team," series weren't gruesome in detail or about neighbors or siblings fighting in front of a live audience. That's why watching "Simon & Simon: Season One" (audio: ***, video: ***, extras: ) brought back memories of a time when sitting in the recliner was a respite from the realities of the world. If you want to return to the campy, un-ultra-special- effects era, when A.J. (Jameson Parker) and Rick (Gerald McRaney, "Major Dad") chased bad guys from San Diego to Tijuana and back again, and when the guns when they did go off didn't sound quite real, this four-disc set is for you. Don't buy it for the extras. There's one recycled piece, "The Great '80s Flashback," which has some great interviews from TV reporters, critics and '80s actors, but it can be found on some releases of 1980s' shows on DVD. So here's to the odd-couple brothers and the creators of "Simon & Simon," who gave us some good shows in a simpler TV lifetime. (Fullscreen, 1981, not rated) Toni Guagenti Cynthia McKinney: conspiracy kook or civil champion? In "American Blackout" (audio: ***, video: ***, extras: **) the former Georgia congresswoman is painted the small, discredited cog in a wider system misleading Americans and the media. The film, which won six film awards including one at Sundance, details McKinney's questioning of Bush's Florida win in 2000, which coincided with thousands of black voters being wrongly identified as felons at the polls. We see her turned into a wacko when, days after the 9-11 attacks, she hints that the government had some prior warnings. We watch Republicans flood the Democratic primary to ouster her in her own party, and then see her, after the 2004 election, wonder aloud why black voters in Ohio were made to wait in long lines in the rain to vote, only to be turned away. It's short on extras, they're good. The anonymous interview with black Capitol Hill Police makes you wonder if her infamous scuffle with Cap Hill Police was about something much bigger. It's the "Fahrenheit 9-11" of black voting. With the ability to mass-produce this stuff, some characters don't last as long as the series they're supposed to star in. It's nice when TV land resurrects an oldie but a goodie, which the former WB did with "Tom and Jerry Tales," (audio: ***, video: ***1/2, extras: 0) on DVD with 12 cartoons from the new TV series on The CW (The WB merged with UPN to form CW, for those of you who didn't know). text: Local chapters of the National Wild Turkey Federation annually host events for the young members of their clubs. Like young male turkeys, the children are affectionately known in federation circles as "jakes." The Tidewater Chapter of the National Wild Turkey Federation last weekend joined with chapters in Suffolk and Wakefield to host the fourth annual Jakes Day at the Bronco Club in Southampton County. More than 30 boys and girls 16 and younger were treated to a day of learning. "It was wet and windy but pretty wild," said Pete Costenbader, president of the Tidewater chapter. Mike Arrington and Robbie Taylor of the Suffolk and Wakefield clubs were the event's main organizers, Costenbader said. "We usually have about 50 or so kids each year, but this was in the midst of the worst part of that storm," Costenbader said. "It's kind of amazing anybody showed up." Those who did got a good education in things such as archery, skeet shooting, marksmanship, fishing and tracking animals. Tommy Baharm, a pro staffer for Primos Hunting Calls, discussed and demonstrated various turkey calls. Costenbader added that Arrington had arranged for prizes such as turkey calls and gun cases for all participating "jakes." Flounder update: The National Marine Fisheries Service has released its flounder catch information for July and August. The figures confirm that Virginia flounder anglers have greatly exceeded their targeted catch for 2006. Virginia was given a target of 616,000 flounder for 2006. Through the end of August, anglers had landed 793,083 flounder. While landings for September through the end of the year generally are low, it is almost certain that Virginia recreational anglers will top 800,000 pounds for the year. That could spell trouble for Virginia anglers next year when fisheries managers must implement a federal order to reduce the entire East Coast catch. According to Rob O'Reilly, assistant chief of fisheries for the Virginia Marine Resources Commission, the service is leaning toward a 2007 reduction of 40 percent to 50 percent from 2006. Exceeding the state catch limit this year could push Virginia's forced reduction toward the high end of that scale. Virginia anglers next year will see lower bag limits, longer minimum lengths, and possibly some season closures. The federal reduction is being ordered to help a continuing plan of helping the East Coast flounder population rebound from about 18,000 pounds in the 1980s to approximately 200,000 pounds in 2010. The VMRC will not be able to start working on several rules options until the final federal numbers are released by the NMFS. Record certified: The 116.5-pound cobia caught in June by Billy Ray Lucas has been certified as an 80-pound line-class world record by the International Game Fish Association. Lucas, of Wilson, N.C., caught the giant just off the Salvo beach. The fight took about 30 minutes. Lucas' fish is now the North Carolina state saltwater cobia record. The 71-inch-long, 32-inch-girth fish is thought to be the fifth-largest cobia ever caught on a rod and reel. Nature's fireworks: Stargazers wanting to catch one of the best meteor showers of the year should look to the eastern sky during the middle of the night next weekend. The Orionids meteor showers are expected to peak around 1 a.m. Saturday. During the peak, observers can expect to see 20 to 40 meteors an hour. The showers will be most visible about halfway between the horizon to overhead. Committee meeting: The Virginia Saltwater Fishing Tournament Committee will meet later this month to discuss possible program changes. The tournament honors anglers for trophy-sized catches and releases of fish meeting minimum standards for a variety of species. Anglers receive their choice of plaques or certificates. The meeting will be held at 6:45 p.m. Oct. 25 in the swimming pool lounge at Marina Shores in Virginia Beach. There will be a brief period for public comment before the meeting. Two of the most important aspects of the meeting each year are potential changes to the minimum standards for awards. Flounder and spot are two of the fish that will receive most of the attention at this year's meeting. There also is a proposal to add blueline tilefish to the awards program. Anglers fishing off Virginia recorded four world records for the species this year. For more information, call . text: No. 8 Tallwood 23, Kempsville 17 VIRGINIA BEACH - Despite a bad cut on his passing hand, quarterback Brian Jackson led Tallwood to Beach District victory Friday that kept the Lions squarely in the playoff hunt. Brian Jackson threw a 77-yard touchdown pass to Aaron Holman on the first play from scrimmage but sustained a badly cut passing hand on the play. He returned to the field, however, and helped Lions win their third consecutive game and improve to 5-1, their best start since going 12-1 in 1998. Jackson, who left for a hospital immediately after the game to receive stitches in the hand, completed 10 of 18 passes for 185 yards and a touchdown and kicked two extra points. The Chiefs scored the game's final touchdown on Kai James' 2-yard catch of a Tahj Taylor pass but couldn't recover the subsequent onside kick with 39 seconds left. Norfolk State at Hampton When: 1:30 p.m. Where: Armstrong Stadium, Hampton Records: Norfolk State, 3-2, 1-2 MEAC; Hampton, 6-0, 4-0. Radio: 88.1 FM, 91.1 FM About Norfolk State: The Spartans hope to bounce back from a 47-10 loss at South Carolina State last weekend with their first-ever win over a I-AA ranked opponent. QB Casey Hansen was sacked five times by the Bulldogs but still leads the MEAC in passing (192 ypg). He has thrown four TD passes but also eight INTs. RB Monte' Anthony has 342 yards and six TDs, and WR James Callaham has 16 catches for 183 yards. LB Maguell Davis has a team-high 31 tackles. The Spartans have committed 10 turnovers and caused three. About Hampton: The Pirates are No. 12 in the Sports Network's I-AA national poll and have won 23 consecutive regular-season games. Hampton has won the teams' past four meetings and 12 of the past 14 and are 4-1 at home against NSU since joining the MEAC in 1995. RB Alonzo Coleman has 446 yards and five touchdowns while his "backup," Kevin Beverly, has 399 yards and five scores. QB Princeton Shepherd has thrown for 923 yards and 11 touchdowns, against one interception. LB Justin Durant has 55 tackles and K Andrew Paterini has converted 8 of 12 field goals. Wake Forest at N.C. State When: Noon Where: Carter-Finley Stadium; Raleigh, N.C. TV: WGNT Radio: 96.7 FM Records: Wake Forest 5-1, 1-1 ACC; N.C. State 3-2, 2-0. About Wake Forest: The Demon Deacons are better than they've been in a long time. But usually mediocre Wake got a lesson in closing the deal last week, when a field goal in the third quarter would've put the Deacs up 17 on No. 12 Clemson. Instead, a botched snap was six the other way, sparking a Tigers' comeback. Wake thinks it ought to be 6-0 and atop the Atlantic Division, and has a chance to pick up that sixth win (and bowl eligibility) as well as get back into the division race. The Deacs rank 14th nationally in scoring defense, allowing less than two touchdowns per game. Offensively, they're led by freshman QB Riley Skinner, the ACC's most efficient passer (68.4 percent completions, 4 TDs and 1 INT). About N.C. State: Since flopping against Akron and Southern Miss, the Wolfpack has been perfect in conference play, knocking off ACC big boys Boston College and Florida State the past two weeks. A win here will keep State in sole possession of first place in the Atlantic and completely cool the "Fire Chuck Amato" talk that heated up last month. QB Daniel Evans has been a key. Since taking over for struggling Marcus Stone, Evans has engineered two wins, throwing for 369 yards, four TDs and only one pick. He's helped by RB Andre Brown, who's averaging 6.4 yards a carry. Still, State needs to up the output, as the Pack ranks 90th or worse nationally in scoring, passing yards and total offense. Favorite: N.C. State by 3 Florida State at Duke When: 1 p.m. Where: Wallace Wade Stadium; Durham, N.C. Records: Florida State 3-2, 1-2 ACC; Duke 0-5, 0-3. Outlook: The Seminoles may be sub-.500 in the league for the first time since Bobby Bowden discovered the word "dadgum," but FSU are heavy favorites to creep back to even against the hapless Blue Devils. The 'Noles will try to strengthen their running game, which ranks 87th in the nation, and should bury an inept Duke offense. While the Seminoles rank 17th in run defense and 18th in total defense nationally, the Devils are 100th or worse in every major offensive category. FSU figures to tee off on true freshman QB Thaddeus Lewis and Duke should remain winless. Favorite: Florida State by 22-1/2 Maryland at Virginia When: 3:30 p.m. Where: Scott Stadium, Charlottesville Records: Maryland 3-2, 0-1 ACC; Virginia 2-4, 1-1. Radio: 850 AM About Maryland: The Terps pushed Georgia Tech to the brink before falling 27-23 in Atlanta last week. TB Lance Ball rushed for 116 yards, Maryland's first 100-yard effort this year. The offense has been slow getting started, averaging 305 yards and 22 points a game, even with coach Ralph Friedgen taking on coordinator duties. Turnovers have hurt. Maryland ranks 10th in the ACC and 114th in the nation in TO margin. QB Sam Hollenbach has just five TD passes and the WRs are young. Look for Maryland to ride Ball, who rushed for 163 yards against Virginia last year. Adam Podlesh, one of the best punters in the ACC, gives Maryland a possible edge in the field-position game. The defense has been vulnerable against the run (169 ypg), but better against the pass, with a veteran secondary leading the way. Maryland has not won in Charlottesville since 1990. About Virginia: As poorly as the season has gone, Virginia is 1-1 in the ACC and is looking at this three-game homestand as a fresh start. If the Cavaliers are to salvage something of the season, this is the time to begin. Virginia has won seven straight over Maryland at home and 11 of the past 14 overall. After taking a step forward with a convincing win over Duke, Virginia took two steps back in last week's loss at East Carolina. The Cavs allowed a season-high 432 yards, including 208 on the ground. Still, the defense is No. 32 in the nation. DEs Chris Long and Jeffrey Fitzgerald are two of the best in the ACC and LB Jon Copper has been productive. The Cavaliers need better play up the middle and in the secondary. The offense continues to creep along under redshirt freshman QB Jameel Sewell, though the running game has shown signs of life the past two weeks. The receiving corps has been a disappointment, with several drops last week, and Virginia has been unable to get the TEs involved downfield, as hoped. Favorite: Maryland by 3-1/2 S. The Tar Heels have been outscored 79-14 in their past two outings and are allowing 35 points per game on the season. They've yet to beat a Division I-A team. South Florida has a stingy defense that allows 16.3 points per game. The Bulls are no offensive power but everyone has moved the ball on North Carolina. Favorite: South Florida by 3-1/2 Fla. The Hurricanes are in the midst of a soft portion of their schedule, with Duke next week, and are using these games to tune up for a late-reason run.
